{"title_page": "California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      = Department of Corrections\n| abbreviation    = CDCR\n| fictional       =\n| patch           = CA - DCR.png\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            = Seal of the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation.png\n| logocaption     =\n| badge           = CA - DOCR Badge Patch.png\n| badgecaption    = Badge Patch of the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation\n| flag            =\n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           =\n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = {{start date and age|1885}}\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      = California Department of Corrections,<br />California Youth Authority\n| dissolved       =\n| superseding     =\n| employees       = 66,800\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          = US$11.3 billion (2017/2018)\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     = USA\n| national        =\n| federal         =\n| international   =\n| divtype         = State\n| divname         = California\n| divdab          =\n| subdivtype      =\n| subdivname      =\n| subdivdab       =\n| map             = California in United States.svg\n| mapcaption      = Jurisdiction of the Department, excluding when transporting detainees in Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-289.html#NRS289Sec230 |date=1993 |accessdate=July 16, 2018|publisher=State of [[Nevada]]|title=NRS\u2002289.230\u2002\u2002California correctional officer.}}</ref>\n| sizearea        = {{convert|163696|sqmi|km2}}\n| sizepopulation  = 39,536,653 (2017 est.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/CA,US/PST045217 |date=December 21, 2017 |accessdate=December 21, 2017|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|title=California: Population estimates}}</ref>\n| legaljuris      = opsjuris\n| governingbody   =\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| military        =\n| provost         =\n| gendarmerie     =\n| religious       =\n| speciality      =\n| secret          =\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Sacramento, California]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| multinational   =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Ralph Diaz\n| chief1position  = Secretary\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| stations        =\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =Patrol Cars\n| vehicles1       =\u2022Ford Explorer Police Interceptor              \u2022Ford Crown Victoria-Police         \u2022Ford Taurus-Police \n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| animal2type     =\n| animals2        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = {{URL|www.cdcr.ca.gov}}\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\nThe '''California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation''' ('''CDCR''') is the agency of the [[government of California]] responsible for the operation of the California state prison and [[parole]] systems. Its headquarters are in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].\n\n== Staff size ==\nCDCR is the 3rd largest law enforcement agency in the United States behind the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] (CBP) \nwhich is an arm of Dept of Homeland Security (DHS), and the [[New York City Police Department]], which employ approximately 66,000 federal officers and 42,000 police officers respectively. CDCR correctional officers are sworn law enforcement officers with peace officer powers.\n\nAs of 2013, CDCR employed approximately 24,000 peace officers (state correctional officers), 1,800 state parole agents, and 200 criminal investigators/special agents.\n\n\n\n'''Secretary Ralph Diaz'''\n\nRalph Diaz was appointed by Governor Gavin Newsom as Secretary for the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation (CDCR) on March 27, 2019. Most recently, he served as Undersecretary of Operations, Deputy Director of Facility Operations, and Associate Director of High Security Institutions. Before that, Mr. Diaz served as a prison Warden, Correctional Counselor Supervisor, and Correctional Counselor, after starting his career as a Correctional Officer in 1991. \n\nMr. Diaz has the honor and privilege to lead over 60,000 of the nation\u2019s finest correctional professionals, who provide outstanding levels of rehabilitative services to the offenders in our care. \n\nWith more than 29 years of diverse correctional experience, Mr. Diaz has seen first-hand how restorative justice practices can transform communities inside and outside prison walls. He believes in a holistic approach to corrections that offers a variety of educational, vocational, and therapeutic programs to offenders while also stressing individual accountability and respecting and honoring victims of crime.\n\nMr. Diaz has been instrumental in developing policies focused on staff well-being and professional development, while empowering them to serve as role models and mentors to all.<ref>ps://www.cdcr.ca.gov/about-cdcr/secretary CDCR Website<ref>\n==History==\nIn 1851, California activated its first state-run institution. This institution was a 268-ton wooden ship named ''The Waban'', and was anchored in the [[San Francisco Bay]].<ref>[[California Department of Justice]]. [http://ag.ca.gov/cjsc/glance/timeline/tl4pg.pdf California Criminal Justice Time Line 1822\u20132000] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528223733/http://ag.ca.gov/cjsc/glance/timeline/tl4pg.pdf |date=May 28, 2008 }}. Accessed April 27, 2008.</ref> The prison ship housed 30 inmates who subsequently constructed [[San Quentin State Prison]], which opened in 1852 with approximately 68 inmates.<ref name=Reed>Reed, Dan. \"Killer Location May Doom San Quentin Prison. Also Calling It Outdated, State to Consider Razing Infamous Bayside Penitentiary for Housing\". ''San Jose Mercury News'', August 20, 2001.</ref>\n\nSince 1852, the Department has activated thirty-one prisons across the state. CDCR's history dates back to 1912, when the agency was called California State Detentions Bureau. In 1951 it was renamed California Department of Corrections. In 2004 it was renamed California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation (CDCR).\n\nIn 2016-2017 it cost an average of $70,836 to house an inmate for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lao.ca.gov/PolicyAreas/CJ/6_cj_inmatecost|title=Legislative Analyst's Office|website=www.lao.ca.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\n===Reorganization (2000s)===\n\n{{See also|California Division of Juvenile Justice }}\n\nIn 2004, a Corrections Independent Review Panel suggested \"Reorganizing the Youth and Adult Correctional Agency\".<ref name=IRP>Corrections Independent Review Panel. [http://cpr.ca.gov/report/indrpt/corr/report/intro.htm Reforming Corrections.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401134351/http://cpr.ca.gov/report/indrpt/corr/report/intro.htm |date=April 1, 2008 }} June 2004.</ref>  The Agency had consisted of \"the Department of Corrections, the Department of the Youth Authority, the Board of Prison Terms, the Board of Corrections, the Commission on Correctional [[Peace Officer Standards and Training]], the Narcotic Addict Evaluation Board and the Youth Authority Board.\"<ref  name=Schwarzenegger>[http://gov.ca.gov/index.php?/press-release/1935/ Governor Schwarzenegger Signs Legislation to Transform California's Prison System].  Press release, May 10, 2005.</ref>\n\nCalifornia Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger made a reorganization plan public in January 2005 implementing many of the recommendations of the panel but without \"a citizens commission overseeing the state's entire correctional operation.\"<ref>Furillo, Andy. \"Prisons plan shifts power to agency chief\". ''Sacramento Bee'', January 7, 2005.</ref> The reorganization became effective on July 1, 2005.<ref  name=Schwarzenegger/> The CDCR superseded the:<ref>California Government Code 12838.5</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:CA - CDCR Map.png|thumb|450px|A map of CDCR locations across California.]]\n\n===Headquarters===\nNewsletter http://www.insidecdcr.ca.gov/\n\n===Divisions and boards===\n\n* [[California Adult Operations Division]]\n* [[California Adult Parole Division]]\n* [[California Adult Programs Division]]\n* [[California Board of Parole Hearings]]\n* [[California Council on Mentally Ill Offenders (COMIO)]]\n* [[California Corrections Standards Authority]]\n* [[California Juvenile Justice]]\n* [[CPHCS Contract Branch]]\n* [[California Prison Industry Authority|Prison Industry Authority]] (CALPIA)\n* [[State Commission on Juvenile Justice]]\n* [[Division of Rehabilitative Programs]] (DRP)\n\n===Facilities===\n{{See also|List of California state prisons}}\nCDCR operates all state institutions, oversees a variety of community correctional facilities and camps, and monitors all parolees during their entry back into society.\n\n===Institutions===\nAccording to the Department's official Web site, \"Currently there are 33 [[List of California state prisons|adult correctional institutions]], 13 adult community correctional facilities, and eight juvenile facilities in California that house more than 165,000 adult offenders and nearly 3,200 juvenile offenders.\"<ref name=Visitors>CDCR Division of Adult Institutions. [http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/index.html Visitors Information Page.] Retrieved November 30, 2007.</ref> This inmate population makes the CDCR the largest state-run prison system in the United States.<ref name=MooreNYT>Moore, Solomon. [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/24/us/24calif.html ''New Court to Address California Prison Crowding\"]. ''The New York Times'', July 24, 2007.</ref>\n\nRegarding adult prisons, CDCR has the task of receiving and housing inmates that were convicted of [[felony]] crimes within the State of California. When an adult inmate arrives at a state prison, he/she is assigned a classification based on his/her committed offense. Each prison is designed to house different varieties of inmate offenders, from Level I inmates to Level IV inmates; the higher the level, the higher risk the inmate poses. Selected prisons within the state are equipped with security housing units, reception centers, and/or \"condemned\" units.  These security levels are defined as follows:<ref name=CDCR2007>California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation. [http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/docs/20071015-WEBmapbooklet.pdf California's Correctional Facilities] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214123130/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/docs/20071015-WEBmapbooklet.pdf |date=December 14, 2007 }}. October 15, 2007.</ref>\n\n* Level I: \"Open dormitories without a secure perimeter.\"\n* Level II: \"Open dormitories with secure perimeter fences and armed coverage.\"\n* Level III: \"Individual cells, fenced perimeters and armed coverage.\"\n* Level IV: \"Cells, fenced or walled perimeters, electronic security, more staff and armed officers both inside and outside the installation.\"\n* Security Housing Unit (SHU): \"The most secure area within a Level IV prison designed to provide maximum coverage.\"  These are designed to handle inmates who cannot be housed with the general population of inmates. This includes inmates who are validated prison gang members, gang bosses or shot callers, etc.\n* Reception Center (RC): \"Provides short term housing to process, classify and evaluate incoming inmates.\"\n* Condemned (Cond): \"Holds inmates with [[Capital punishment|death sentences]].\"\n\n'''<big>Death Row</big>'''\n\nCondemned male prisoners are held at [[San Quentin State Prison]]. Condemned female prisoners are held at the [[Central California Women's Facility]]. Executions take place at San Quentin. The State of California took full control of capital punishment in 1891. Originally, executions took place at San Quentin and at [[Folsom State Prison]]. Folsom's last execution occurred on December 3, 1937.<ref>\"[http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/reports_research/historycapital.html History of Capital Punishment in California] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724032245/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/reports_research/historycapital.html|date=July 24, 2010}}.\" [[California Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on August 16, 2010.</ref> In previous eras the [[California Institution for Women]] housed the death row for women.<ref>\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19720215&id=mAMdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QJwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7260,2543785 Court Ruling Won't Mean Bloodbath On Death Row]\". [[Associated Press]] at the ''[[Tuscaloosa News]]''. Tuesday February 15, 1972. p. 10. Retrieved on [[Google News]] (6/15) on March 27, 2013. \"There are five women under a sentence of death. Three of Manson's convicted accomplices, Susan Atkins, Leslie Houten, and Patricia Krenwinkel, are in a special women's section of the row built at the California Institute for Women at Frontera.\"</ref>[[File:SanQuentinSP.jpg|thumb|250px|[[San Quentin State Prison]].]]\n\n===Parole===\nAccording to the Department's official Web site, \"there are more than 148,000 adult parolees and 3,800 juvenile parolees supervised by the CDCR.\"<ref name=Visitors/> A 2002 article found that \"California's growth in the numbers of people on parole supervision\u2014and in the numbers whose parole has been revoked\u2014has far exceeded the growth in the rest of the nation.\"<ref name=Travis>Travis, Jeremy, and Lawrence, Sarah. [http://www.urban.org/UploadedPDF/CA_parole_exp.pdf California's Parole Experiment.] California Journal, August 2002.</ref> California accounted for 12 percent of the U.S. population but 18% of the U.S. parole population, and almost 90,000 California parolees returned to prison in 2000.<ref name=Travis/>\n\nAt San Quentin, the non-profit organization [[California Reentry Program]] \"helps inmates re-enter society after they serve their sentences.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Shelah | last= Moody | title=California Reentry Program gives ex-cons a second chance | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/12/09/LV92TOP61.DTL | work=San Francisco Chronicle | date=December 9, 2007 | accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==CDCR Peace Officers==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2012}}\n\nCorrectional Officers are peace officers per California penal code sections 830.5, as their primary duties are to provide public safety and correctional services in and outside of state prison grounds, state-operated medical facilities, and camps while engaged in the performance of their duties.\n\nThe primary duties of these officers include, but are not limited to, providing public safety and law enforcement services in and around California's adult and youth institutions, fire camps, and state-operated medical facilities and hospitals, and community correctional facilities. These officers also monitor and supervise parolees who are released back into the general public. Other primary duties include investigation and apprehension of institutional escapees and parolees at large (PAL), prison gangs, statewide narcotics enforcement and investigations (involving institutions), etc.\n\n===Correctional Peace Officer Academy===\nCDCR Peace Officers are trained to become Sworn Peace Officers of the State of California at the Basic Correctional Peace Officer Academy located in [[Galt, California]]. Cadets must complete a 12-week formal and comprehensive training program. The curriculum consists of 640 hours (four months) of training. Instruction includes but is not limited to firearms, chemical agents, non-lethal impact weapons, arrest and control techniques, state law and department policies and procedures.\n\nCadets must also successfully complete the [[Peace Officer Standards and Training]] (POST) minimum requirement course. Upon completion of the academy, cadets are sworn in as CDCR peace officers. Upon assignment to their work institution or location, these officers also undergo further training for two years as vocational apprentices (one year of which is spent on probation). Upon completion of their two-year training they are then considered regular state correctional peace officers (CDCR officers)<ref name=acad>{{cite web | url = http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Career_Opportunities/POR/COTraining.html | title = Correctional Officer Training | work = Department of Corrections & Rehabilitation | accessdate = April 27, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080416205837/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Career_Opportunities/POR/COTraining.html | archivedate = April 16, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Fugitive Apprehension Team ===\n\nAn elite and low-profile unit within CDCR is the Fugitive Apprehension Team or FAT which is made up of just over eighty agents who are assigned to offices throughout the state. FAT agents are criminal investigators and are teamed with the Warrants Unit of the United States Marshals Service (USMS) in locating and apprehending individuals wanted for high-violence offenses, whether under the jurisdiction of CDCR or local agencies. FAT agents provide services to local agencies whose resources do not allow them to pursue violent offenders who have fled their jurisdictions, to parole violators wanted for violent offenses, and individuals wanted under federal warrants. Some of the agents have powers that extend beyond the State of California as they are also sworn special deputies of the USMS. FAT agents are highly trained in high-risk warrant service execution and must complete a special academy to become members of the \"Teams.\" Members of these teams are kept low-profile for security reasons, as their nature is to conduct investigations in locating violent fugitives and executing their apprehension on a timely basis.\n\nFAT shares a sentimental affiliation with the historic California State Rangers, who were created in May 1853 by a California Legislative Act and organized by Captain Harry Love, to apprehend dangerous offenders of the time. In August 1853, after having fulfilled their purpose, the Rangers were mustered out of service. The affiliation that FAT shares, although remotely, is that in July 1996 the California State Legislature enacted specific funds earmarked via the Department of Corrections to create fugitive teams to locate and bring to justice parole violators, the most violent offenders of modern times.\n\n==Officers killed while on duty==\nAccording to the Officer Down Memorial Page Web site, since the inception of what is currently CDCR, 33 employees have been killed in the line of duty.<ref>[http://www.odmp.org/agency/499-california-department-of-corrections-and-rehabilitation-california The Officer Down Memorial Page] February 2009</ref> Of these, 20 have been killed by inmates. Seventeen were custody employees, and three were non-custody employees who supervised inmates working in industrial areas. Fifteen deaths were from stab wounds, two were from gunshot wounds, two were from bludgeoning, and one was from being thrown from a tier.<ref>{{cite web|last=Data Analysis Unit|title=EMPLOYEES KILLED BY INMATES January 1952 through December 2011|url=http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Reports_Research/Offender_Information_Services_Branch/Annual/Beh5/BEH5d2011.pdf|publisher=[[CDCR]]|accessdate=March 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|}}\n\n\n==<big>Special Service Unit</big>==\nIn addition to correctional officers, CDCR employs a small group of special agents<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chaddock |first1=Don |title=OCS Special Agent Karen Mory shatters preconceptions |url=https://www.insidecdcr.ca.gov/2018/07/ocs-special-agent-karen-mory-shatters-preconceptions/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314014927/https://www.insidecdcr.ca.gov/2018/07/ocs-special-agent-karen-mory-shatters-preconceptions/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 March 2019 |website=Inside CDCR |publisher=CDCR |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> (criminal investigators) who are assigned to offices throughout the state.These investigators are part of an elite unit known as the Special Service Unit or simply SSU. They have full-time peace officer powers throughout the state under Penal Code Section 803.2. SSU agents conduct criminal investigations involving parolees and inmates,  monitor prison gangs, gather intelligence and conduct narcotics enforcement.  Special agents work closely with other law enforcement agencies, such as the Federal Bureau of Investigation, California Department of Justice and local police and sheriff departments. SSU special agents hold the state equivalency of a CDCR captain.  As confidential employees, they are able to keep a low profile and small footprint while carrying out very high-profile cases.\n\nThe Special Service Unit was formed in 1964, at the request of then-California Governor Edmund Brown. Sadly, the formation of the unit is said to have evolved after the March 9, 1963 kidnapping of two Los Angeles police officers. The kidnapping and subsequent murder of one of the officers was committed by two state parolees, Gregory Powell and Jimmy Lee Smith (a.k.a., Jimmy Youngblood). LAPD officers Ian Campbell and Karl Hettinger conducted a routine traffic stop on Powell and Smith in the Hollywood area.  As the two officers approached the car, they were kidnapped at gunpoint by the two parolees and forced into Powell's car. They were driven north from Los Angeles to an onion field near Bakersfield, where Officer Campbell was fatally shot.  Officer Hettinger was able to escape.\n\nIn the police investigation that ensued after the incident, the ability of LAPD detectives to get timely and necessary information from the Department of Corrections was severely hampered, ostensibly by the size and bureaucracy of the department. Detectives needed a way to obtain information quickly and have the assistance of the CDCR resources. Because of this tragic incident and the legislative conferences afterward, a decision was made to form the Special Service Unit.\n\nCharles Casey, who was an assistant director with CDCR at the time, learned of a unit within the New York Department of Corrections that seemed to bridge the gap between New York state parole services and local law enforcement. Casey met with Russell H. Oswald, chairman of the New York State Parole Board, who was the founder of the Bureau of Special Services within the New York parole division. Based upon his study and evaluation of the Bureau of Special Services, Casey came back to California and designed a similar unit, calling it the Special Service Unit. After the legislature approved its formation, the unit officially began services in 1964.\n\nThe unit serves as the primary investigative unit for CDCR on cases that stem from the prison or state parolees and affect the street. According to its official description, SSU \"conducts the major criminal investigations and prosecutions, criminal apprehension efforts of prison escapees and parolees wanted for serious and violent felonies, is the primary departmental gang management unit, conducts complex gang-related investigations of inmates and parolees suspected of criminal gang activity, and is the administrative investigative and law enforcement liaison unit.\" In layman's terms, this means the unit does anything asked of it to keep communities safe.\n\n<gallery>\n</gallery>\n\n==High Profile Cases Involving SSU==\nThroughout its fifty-year history, the Special Service Unit has been quietly involved in numerous high-profile cases.  One such example is the Patricia Hearst kidnapping by the Symbionese Liberation Army (SLA) in 1974. The SLA was a radical left-wing organization formed in Soledad Prison by Donald DeFreeze. In 1973 Defreeze escaped from prison and was leading the SLA on the streets when they kidnapped Hearst. The day after Hearst's kidnapping, special agents from the unit's San Francisco office provided police with photographs of suspects who matched the overall description of one of the abductors. Thanks to photographs supplied by SSU, DeFreeze was positively identified as one of Hearst's abductors. That identification led to a lengthy investigation of SLA and its origin behind prison walls.\n\nAnother example is the high-profile murders that shook Los Angeles in the late sixties. The murders were committed by members of Charles Manson's cult and came to be known as Helter Skelter. During the course of the investigation into the cult, SSU special agents were requested by Los Angeles Police to interview Bruce Davis, a Manson follower who had been convicted of the 1969 Gary Hinman murder in Los Angeles. Davis was a Manson devotee whom police were trying to turn as an informant into many of the open murders linked to the Manson Family. \n\nOn January 26, 2001, San Francisco resident Diane Whipple was attacked and killed by two large Presa Canario dogs in the hallway of her apartment building. The dogs, named Bane and Hera, were owned by Whipple's neighbors, Marjorie Knoller and Robert Noel. The dogs' actual owner, Paul Schneider, was a high-ranking member of the Aryan Brotherhood prison gang who was serving a life sentence in Pelican Bay State Prison. The Special Service Unit had been investigating the Aryan Brotherhood and its illegal dog breeding business for several months prior to the death of Whipple. SSU was able to assist local law enforcement during the investigation and prosecution of Knoller and Noel.\n\nIn August 2009, Phillip Garrido was arrested in Antioch, Calif.,  for the kidnapping of Jaycee Dugard. He had kidnapped her eighteen years prior and kept her in captivity. The Hayward (Calif.) police department had interest in Garrido as it related to the 1988 kidnapping of nine-year-old Michaela Garecht.  Special agents from SSU assisted the detectives from the Hayward Police Department in the ensuing investigation. In 2011, they assisted in conducting interviews with Garrido and his wife, Nancy Garrido, who had both been sentenced to state prison in California. \n\nIn August 2014, convicted murderer Scott Landers escaped from the back of a CDCR transport van while on the Interstate 5 freeway just north of Atwater, Calif. Landers had been convicted of the stabbing of a 61-year-old man in Riverside, Calif. and was serving twenty-five years to life. Upon his escape, members of the elite Special Service Unit were called in from across the state to lead the investigation. Within twenty-four hours, the escaped murderer was caught and brought back to CDCR custody.\n\n==Current Structure of SSU==\n\nThe current configuration of the Special Service Unit remains true to its origins\u2014small and mobile. As of 2018, CDCR reports there are only thirty SSU special agents. They are based throughout California in clandestine, off-site locations. Every agent is equipped with tactical and surveillance equipment and is ready to respond anywhere within the state at a moment's notice.\n\nIn 2005, CDCR began to consolidate various divisions and units in an effort to realign its organizational structure. During that time the Office of Correctional Safety (OCS) was created, which serves as the \"special operations division\" for the department. Within the OCS are groups such as the Fugitive Apprehension Team (FAT) and the Emergency Operations Unit (EOU). SSU became a branch of OCS as well, which elevated the training and tactical acumen for all of the special agents. With the merger of the EOU unit with SSU, special agents were responsible for attaining a higher level of tactical firearms proficiency as well as tactical high-risk entry training.\n\nServing as the \"detective unit\" for the Department of Corrections, SSU special agents are responsible for keeping current on the latest investigative techniques and current case law.  Special agents often work hand-in-hand with law enforcement investigators from all branches of government, city, county and federal.  Many SSU agents are assigned to regional task forces throughout California and a handful are cross-designated as federal task force officers with such federal partners as the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA), [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) and the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms]] (BATF).\n\n\n==Issues==\n\n===Prison health care===\n{{See also|Plata v. Brown|Coleman v. Brown}}\n\nThere are at multiple ongoing lawsuits over medical care in the California prison system. ''[[Plata v. Brown]]'' is a federal [[class action]] [[civil rights]] lawsuit alleging unconstitutionally inadequate medical services, and as a result of a [[stipulation]] between the plaintiffs and the state, the court issued an [[injunction]] requiring defendants to provide \"only the minimum level of medical care required under the Eighth Amendment.\" However, three years after approving the stipulation as an order of the court, the court conducted an evidentiary hearing that revealed the continued existence of appalling conditions arising from defendants\u2019 failure to provide adequate medical care to California inmates. As a result, the court ruled in June 2005 and issued an order on October 3, 2005 putting the CDCR's medical health care delivery system in [[receivership]], citing the \"depravity\" of the system.<ref>{{cite news | first= James | last= Sterngold | title= U.S. seizes state prison health care | url= http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2005/07/01/MNGOCDHPP71.DTL | work= San Francisco Chronicle | date= July 5, 2005 | accessdate=December 21, 2007 }}</ref> In February 2006, the judge appointed Robert Sillen to the position<ref>{{cite news | first= Solomon | last= Moore | title= Using Muscle to Improve Health Care for Prisoners | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/27/us/27prisons.html | work= New York Times | date=August 27, 2007 | accessdate=December 21, 2007 }}</ref> and Sillen was replaced by J. Clark Kelso in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web | last = Kagan | first = Racheal | title = CPR PRESS RELEASE: Judge Appoints New Prison Health Care Receiver, 01/23/08 | date = January 23, 2008 | url = http://cprinc.org/docs/press/PR_012308_NewReceiver.pdf | format = pdf | accessdate = February 9, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100926003420/http://cprinc.org/docs/press/PR_012308_NewReceiver.pdf | archivedate = September 26, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n''[[Coleman v. Brown]]'' is a federal [[class action]] [[civil rights]] lawsuit alleging unconstitutionally inadequate mental health care, filed on April 23, 1990. On September 13, 1995 the court found the delivery of mental health care violated the [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], and issued an order for injunctive relief requiring defendants to develop plans to remedy the constitutional violations under the supervision of a [[special master]].\n\nFollowing the Governor's issuance of the State of Emergency Proclamation, the plaintiffs in ''Plata'' and ''Coleman'' filed motions to convene a three-judge court to limit the prison population. On July 23, 2007 both the ''Plata'' and ''Coleman'' courts granted the plaintiff's motions and recommended that the cases be assigned to the same three-judge court.<ref name=\"MooreNYT\"/> The Chief Judge of the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit agreed and, on July 26, 2007, convened the instant three-judge district court pursuant to {{usc|28|2284}}.\n\nAs of 2008\u201309 fiscal year, the state of California spent approximately $16,000 per inmate per year on prison health care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lao.ca.gov/handouts/crimjust/2010/Correctional_health_care_03_18_10.pdf|title=Overview of Adult Correctional Health Care Spending}}</ref> This amount was by far the largest in the country and more than triple the $4,400 spent per inmate in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bjs.ojp.usdoj.gov/content/pub/pdf/spe01.pdf|title=State Prison Expenditures, 2001}}</ref> The state with the second largest prison population in the country, Texas, spent less than $4,000 per inmate per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://universityofcalifornia.edu/sites/uchealth/2010/05/20/prison-health-update/|title=Prison health update}}</ref>\n\n==Union: California Correctional Peace Officers Association==\n{{Further|California Correctional Peace Officers Association }}\nOfficers of the department are represented by the California Correctional Peace Officers Association (the CCPOA). It was founded in 1957 and its stated goals include the protection and safety of officers, and the advocation of laws, funding and policies to improve work operations and protect public safety. The union has had its controversies over the years, including criticism of its large contributions to former California Governor Gray Davis.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}} Since the [[California recall election, 2003]], the CCPOA has been a vocal critic of Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}\n\nIn June 2008, the union came under investigation from both the [[California Office of the Inspector General]] and the CDCR for its role in the hiring of a 21-year-old parolee by [[Minorities In Law Enforcement]], an affiliate of CCPOA.<ref>{{cite news | first= Andy | last= Furillo | title= Chief of CCPOA union, Mike Jimenez defends hiring of parolee | url= http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/1029448.html | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080625105018/http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/1029448.html | archivedate= June 25, 2008 | df= mdy-all }}</ref> Upon conclusion of investigations by both agencies, no wrongdoing was found.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|California}}\n*[[List of law enforcement agencies in California]]\n\n'''National:'''\n*[[List of United States state correction agencies]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/}}\n* [https://govt.westlaw.com/calregs/Browse/Home/California/CaliforniaCodeofRegulations?guid=I090873D0D47311DEBC02831C6D6C108E Crime Prevention and Corrections] in the [[California Code of Regulations]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.yaca.state.ca.us/ California Youth and Adult Corrections Authority] (Archive)\n* [http://www.ccpoa.org/ California Correctional Peace Officers Association]\n* [http://ca-reentry.org/ California Reentry Program]\n\n{{California State Agencies}}\n{{State prisons in California}}\n{{Incarceration in the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:California Department of Corrections And Rehabilitation}}\n[[Category:Penal system in California]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:State corrections departments of the United States]]\n[[Category:State law enforcement agencies of California|Corrections and Rehabilitation]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation\n| nativename      =\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      = Department of Corrections\n| abbreviation    = CDCR\n| fictional       =\n| patch           = CA - DCR.png\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            = Seal of the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation.png\n| logocaption     =\n| badge           = CA - DOCR Badge Patch.png\n| badgecaption    = Badge Patch of the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation\n| flag            =\n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           =\n| mottotranslated =\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = {{start date and age|1885}}\n| formedmonthday  =\n| preceding1      = California Department of Corrections,<br />California Youth Authority\n| dissolved       =\n| superseding     =\n| employees       = 66,800\n| volunteers      =\n| budget          = US$11.3 billion (2017/2018)\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = United States\n| countryabbr     = USA\n| national        =\n| federal         =\n| international   =\n| divtype         = State\n| divname         = California\n| divdab          =\n| subdivtype      =\n| subdivname      =\n| subdivdab       =\n| map             = California in United States.svg\n| mapcaption      = Jurisdiction of the Department, excluding when transporting detainees in Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leg.state.nv.us/NRS/NRS-289.html#NRS289Sec230 |date=1993 |accessdate=July 16, 2018|publisher=State of [[Nevada]]|title=NRS\u2002289.230\u2002\u2002California correctional officer.}}</ref>\n| sizearea        = {{convert|163696|sqmi|km2}}\n| sizepopulation  = 39,536,653 (2017 est.)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/CA,US/PST045217 |date=December 21, 2017 |accessdate=December 21, 2017|publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]]|title=California: Population estimates}}</ref>\n| legaljuris      = opsjuris\n| governingbody   =\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| military        =\n| provost         =\n| gendarmerie     =\n| religious       =\n| speciality      =\n| secret          =\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Sacramento, California]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| multinational   =\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      = Ralph Diaz\n| chief1position  = Secretary\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    =\n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| stations        =\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =Patrol Cars\n| vehicles1       =\u2022Ford Explorer Police Interceptor              \u2022Ford Crown Victoria-Police         \u2022Ford Taurus-Police \n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| animal2type     =\n| animals2        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = {{URL|www.cdcr.ca.gov}}\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\nThe '''California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation''' ('''CDCR''') is the agency of the [[government of California]] responsible for the operation of the California state prison and [[parole]] systems. Its headquarters are in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]].\n\n== Staff size ==\nCDCR is the 3rd largest law enforcement agency in the United States behind the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] (CBP) \nwhich is an arm of Dept of Homeland Security (DHS), and the [[New York City Police Department]], which employ approximately 66,000 federal officers and 42,000 police officers respectively. CDCR correctional officers are sworn law enforcement officers with peace officer powers.\n\nAs of 2013, CDCR employed approximately 24,000 peace officers (state correctional officers), 1,800 state parole agents, and 200 criminal investigators/special agents.\n\n\n\n'''Secretary Ralph Diaz'''\n\nRalph Diaz was appointed by Governor Gavin Newsom as Secretary for the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation (CDCR) on March 27, 2019. Most recently, he served as Undersecretary of Operations, Deputy Director of Facility Operations, and Associate Director of High Security Institutions. Before that, Mr. Diaz served as a prison Warden, Correctional Counselor Supervisor, and Correctional Counselor, after starting his career as a Correctional Officer in 1991. \n\nMr. Diaz has the honor and privilege to lead over 60,000 of the nation\u2019s finest correctional professionals, who provide outstanding levels of rehabilitative services to the offenders in our care. \n\nWith more than 29 years of diverse correctional experience, Mr. Diaz has seen first-hand how restorative justice practices can transform communities inside and outside prison walls. He believes in a holistic approach to corrections that offers a variety of educational, vocational, and therapeutic programs to offenders while also stressing individual accountability and respecting and honoring victims of crime.\n\nMr. Diaz has been instrumental in developing policies focused on staff well-being and professional development, while empowering them to serve as role models and mentors to all.\n\n==History==\nIn 1851, California activated its first state-run institution. This institution was a 268-ton wooden ship named ''The Waban'', and was anchored in the [[San Francisco Bay]].<ref>[[California Department of Justice]]. [http://ag.ca.gov/cjsc/glance/timeline/tl4pg.pdf California Criminal Justice Time Line 1822\u20132000] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528223733/http://ag.ca.gov/cjsc/glance/timeline/tl4pg.pdf |date=May 28, 2008 }}. Accessed April 27, 2008.</ref> The prison ship housed 30 inmates who subsequently constructed [[San Quentin State Prison]], which opened in 1852 with approximately 68 inmates.<ref name=Reed>Reed, Dan. \"Killer Location May Doom San Quentin Prison. Also Calling It Outdated, State to Consider Razing Infamous Bayside Penitentiary for Housing\". ''San Jose Mercury News'', August 20, 2001.</ref>\n\nSince 1852, the Department has activated thirty-one prisons across the state. CDCR's history dates back to 1912, when the agency was called California State Detentions Bureau. In 1951 it was renamed California Department of Corrections. In 2004 it was renamed California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation (CDCR).\n\nIn 2016-2017 it cost an average of $70,836 to house an inmate for one year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lao.ca.gov/PolicyAreas/CJ/6_cj_inmatecost|title=Legislative Analyst's Office|website=www.lao.ca.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-03-18}}</ref>\n\n===Reorganization (2000s)===\n\n{{See also|California Division of Juvenile Justice }}\n\nIn 2004, a Corrections Independent Review Panel suggested \"Reorganizing the Youth and Adult Correctional Agency\".<ref name=IRP>Corrections Independent Review Panel. [http://cpr.ca.gov/report/indrpt/corr/report/intro.htm Reforming Corrections.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401134351/http://cpr.ca.gov/report/indrpt/corr/report/intro.htm |date=April 1, 2008 }} June 2004.</ref>  The Agency had consisted of \"the Department of Corrections, the Department of the Youth Authority, the Board of Prison Terms, the Board of Corrections, the Commission on Correctional [[Peace Officer Standards and Training]], the Narcotic Addict Evaluation Board and the Youth Authority Board.\"<ref  name=Schwarzenegger>[http://gov.ca.gov/index.php?/press-release/1935/ Governor Schwarzenegger Signs Legislation to Transform California's Prison System].  Press release, May 10, 2005.</ref>\n\nCalifornia Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger made a reorganization plan public in January 2005 implementing many of the recommendations of the panel but without \"a citizens commission overseeing the state's entire correctional operation.\"<ref>Furillo, Andy. \"Prisons plan shifts power to agency chief\". ''Sacramento Bee'', January 7, 2005.</ref> The reorganization became effective on July 1, 2005.<ref  name=Schwarzenegger/> The CDCR superseded the:<ref>California Government Code 12838.5</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:CA - CDCR Map.png|thumb|450px|A map of CDCR locations across California.]]\n\n===Headquarters===\nNewsletter http://www.insidecdcr.ca.gov/\n\n===Divisions and boards===\n\n* [[California Adult Operations Division]]\n* [[California Adult Parole Division]]\n* [[California Adult Programs Division]]\n* [[California Board of Parole Hearings]]\n* [[California Council on Mentally Ill Offenders (COMIO)]]\n* [[California Corrections Standards Authority]]\n* [[California Juvenile Justice]]\n* [[CPHCS Contract Branch]]\n* [[California Prison Industry Authority|Prison Industry Authority]] (CALPIA)\n* [[State Commission on Juvenile Justice]]\n* [[Division of Rehabilitative Programs]] (DRP)\n\n===Facilities===\n{{See also|List of California state prisons}}\nCDCR operates all state institutions, oversees a variety of community correctional facilities and camps, and monitors all parolees during their entry back into society.\n\n===Institutions===\nAccording to the Department's official Web site, \"Currently there are 33 [[List of California state prisons|adult correctional institutions]], 13 adult community correctional facilities, and eight juvenile facilities in California that house more than 165,000 adult offenders and nearly 3,200 juvenile offenders.\"<ref name=Visitors>CDCR Division of Adult Institutions. [http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/index.html Visitors Information Page.] Retrieved November 30, 2007.</ref> This inmate population makes the CDCR the largest state-run prison system in the United States.<ref name=MooreNYT>Moore, Solomon. [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/24/us/24calif.html ''New Court to Address California Prison Crowding\"]. ''The New York Times'', July 24, 2007.</ref>\n\nRegarding adult prisons, CDCR has the task of receiving and housing inmates that were convicted of [[felony]] crimes within the State of California. When an adult inmate arrives at a state prison, he/she is assigned a classification based on his/her committed offense. Each prison is designed to house different varieties of inmate offenders, from Level I inmates to Level IV inmates; the higher the level, the higher risk the inmate poses. Selected prisons within the state are equipped with security housing units, reception centers, and/or \"condemned\" units.  These security levels are defined as follows:<ref name=CDCR2007>California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation. [http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/docs/20071015-WEBmapbooklet.pdf California's Correctional Facilities] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214123130/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Visitors/docs/20071015-WEBmapbooklet.pdf |date=December 14, 2007 }}. October 15, 2007.</ref>\n\n* Level I: \"Open dormitories without a secure perimeter.\"\n* Level II: \"Open dormitories with secure perimeter fences and armed coverage.\"\n* Level III: \"Individual cells, fenced perimeters and armed coverage.\"\n* Level IV: \"Cells, fenced or walled perimeters, electronic security, more staff and armed officers both inside and outside the installation.\"\n* Security Housing Unit (SHU): \"The most secure area within a Level IV prison designed to provide maximum coverage.\"  These are designed to handle inmates who cannot be housed with the general population of inmates. This includes inmates who are validated prison gang members, gang bosses or shot callers, etc.\n* Reception Center (RC): \"Provides short term housing to process, classify and evaluate incoming inmates.\"\n* Condemned (Cond): \"Holds inmates with [[Capital punishment|death sentences]].\"\n\n'''<big>Death Row</big>'''\n\nCondemned male prisoners are held at [[San Quentin State Prison]]. Condemned female prisoners are held at the [[Central California Women's Facility]]. Executions take place at San Quentin. The State of California took full control of capital punishment in 1891. Originally, executions took place at San Quentin and at [[Folsom State Prison]]. Folsom's last execution occurred on December 3, 1937.<ref>\"[http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/reports_research/historycapital.html History of Capital Punishment in California] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724032245/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/reports_research/historycapital.html|date=July 24, 2010}}.\" [[California Department of Corrections]]. Retrieved on August 16, 2010.</ref> In previous eras the [[California Institution for Women]] housed the death row for women.<ref>\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19720215&id=mAMdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=QJwEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7260,2543785 Court Ruling Won't Mean Bloodbath On Death Row]\". [[Associated Press]] at the ''[[Tuscaloosa News]]''. Tuesday February 15, 1972. p. 10. Retrieved on [[Google News]] (6/15) on March 27, 2013. \"There are five women under a sentence of death. Three of Manson's convicted accomplices, Susan Atkins, Leslie Houten, and Patricia Krenwinkel, are in a special women's section of the row built at the California Institute for Women at Frontera.\"</ref>[[File:SanQuentinSP.jpg|thumb|250px|[[San Quentin State Prison]].]]\n\n===Parole===\nAccording to the Department's official Web site, \"there are more than 148,000 adult parolees and 3,800 juvenile parolees supervised by the CDCR.\"<ref name=Visitors/> A 2002 article found that \"California's growth in the numbers of people on parole supervision\u2014and in the numbers whose parole has been revoked\u2014has far exceeded the growth in the rest of the nation.\"<ref name=Travis>Travis, Jeremy, and Lawrence, Sarah. [http://www.urban.org/UploadedPDF/CA_parole_exp.pdf California's Parole Experiment.] California Journal, August 2002.</ref> California accounted for 12 percent of the U.S. population but 18% of the U.S. parole population, and almost 90,000 California parolees returned to prison in 2000.<ref name=Travis/>\n\nAt San Quentin, the non-profit organization [[California Reentry Program]] \"helps inmates re-enter society after they serve their sentences.\"<ref>{{cite news | first=Shelah | last= Moody | title=California Reentry Program gives ex-cons a second chance | url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/12/09/LV92TOP61.DTL | work=San Francisco Chronicle | date=December 9, 2007 | accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==CDCR Peace Officers==\n{{unreferenced section|date=November 2012}}\n\nCorrectional Officers are peace officers per California penal code sections 830.5, as their primary duties are to provide public safety and correctional services in and outside of state prison grounds, state-operated medical facilities, and camps while engaged in the performance of their duties.\n\nThe primary duties of these officers include, but are not limited to, providing public safety and law enforcement services in and around California's adult and youth institutions, fire camps, and state-operated medical facilities and hospitals, and community correctional facilities. These officers also monitor and supervise parolees who are released back into the general public. Other primary duties include investigation and apprehension of institutional escapees and parolees at large (PAL), prison gangs, statewide narcotics enforcement and investigations (involving institutions), etc.\n\n===Correctional Peace Officer Academy===\nCDCR Peace Officers are trained to become Sworn Peace Officers of the State of California at the Basic Correctional Peace Officer Academy located in [[Galt, California]]. Cadets must complete a 12-week formal and comprehensive training program. The curriculum consists of 640 hours (four months) of training. Instruction includes but is not limited to firearms, chemical agents, non-lethal impact weapons, arrest and control techniques, state law and department policies and procedures.\n\nCadets must also successfully complete the [[Peace Officer Standards and Training]] (POST) minimum requirement course. Upon completion of the academy, cadets are sworn in as CDCR peace officers. Upon assignment to their work institution or location, these officers also undergo further training for two years as vocational apprentices (one year of which is spent on probation). Upon completion of their two-year training they are then considered regular state correctional peace officers (CDCR officers)<ref name=acad>{{cite web | url = http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Career_Opportunities/POR/COTraining.html | title = Correctional Officer Training | work = Department of Corrections & Rehabilitation | accessdate = April 27, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080416205837/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Career_Opportunities/POR/COTraining.html | archivedate = April 16, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Fugitive Apprehension Team ===\n\nAn elite and low-profile unit within CDCR is the Fugitive Apprehension Team or FAT which is made up of just over eighty agents who are assigned to offices throughout the state. FAT agents are criminal investigators and are teamed with the Warrants Unit of the United States Marshals Service (USMS) in locating and apprehending individuals wanted for high-violence offenses, whether under the jurisdiction of CDCR or local agencies. FAT agents provide services to local agencies whose resources do not allow them to pursue violent offenders who have fled their jurisdictions, to parole violators wanted for violent offenses, and individuals wanted under federal warrants. Some of the agents have powers that extend beyond the State of California as they are also sworn special deputies of the USMS. FAT agents are highly trained in high-risk warrant service execution and must complete a special academy to become members of the \"Teams.\" Members of these teams are kept low-profile for security reasons, as their nature is to conduct investigations in locating violent fugitives and executing their apprehension on a timely basis.\n\nFAT shares a sentimental affiliation with the historic California State Rangers, who were created in May 1853 by a California Legislative Act and organized by Captain Harry Love, to apprehend dangerous offenders of the time. In August 1853, after having fulfilled their purpose, the Rangers were mustered out of service. The affiliation that FAT shares, although remotely, is that in July 1996 the California State Legislature enacted specific funds earmarked via the Department of Corrections to create fugitive teams to locate and bring to justice parole violators, the most violent offenders of modern times.\n\n==Officers killed while on duty==\nAccording to the Officer Down Memorial Page Web site, since the inception of what is currently CDCR, 33 employees have been killed in the line of duty.<ref>[http://www.odmp.org/agency/499-california-department-of-corrections-and-rehabilitation-california The Officer Down Memorial Page] February 2009</ref> Of these, 20 have been killed by inmates. Seventeen were custody employees, and three were non-custody employees who supervised inmates working in industrial areas. Fifteen deaths were from stab wounds, two were from gunshot wounds, two were from bludgeoning, and one was from being thrown from a tier.<ref>{{cite web|last=Data Analysis Unit|title=EMPLOYEES KILLED BY INMATES January 1952 through December 2011|url=http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Reports_Research/Offender_Information_Services_Branch/Annual/Beh5/BEH5d2011.pdf|publisher=[[CDCR]]|accessdate=March 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|}}\n\n\n==<big>Special Service Unit</big>==\nIn addition to correctional officers, CDCR employs a small group of special agents<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chaddock |first1=Don |title=OCS Special Agent Karen Mory shatters preconceptions |url=https://www.insidecdcr.ca.gov/2018/07/ocs-special-agent-karen-mory-shatters-preconceptions/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190314014927/https://www.insidecdcr.ca.gov/2018/07/ocs-special-agent-karen-mory-shatters-preconceptions/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 March 2019 |website=Inside CDCR |publisher=CDCR |accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> (criminal investigators) who are assigned to offices throughout the state.These investigators are part of an elite unit known as the Special Service Unit or simply SSU. They have full-time peace officer powers throughout the state under Penal Code Section 803.2. SSU agents conduct criminal investigations involving parolees and inmates,  monitor prison gangs, gather intelligence and conduct narcotics enforcement.  Special agents work closely with other law enforcement agencies, such as the Federal Bureau of Investigation, California Department of Justice and local police and sheriff departments. SSU special agents hold the state equivalency of a CDCR captain.  As confidential employees, they are able to keep a low profile and small footprint while carrying out very high-profile cases.\n\nThe Special Service Unit was formed in 1964, at the request of then-California Governor Edmund Brown. Sadly, the formation of the unit is said to have evolved after the March 9, 1963 kidnapping of two Los Angeles police officers. The kidnapping and subsequent murder of one of the officers was committed by two state parolees, Gregory Powell and Jimmy Lee Smith (a.k.a., Jimmy Youngblood). LAPD officers Ian Campbell and Karl Hettinger conducted a routine traffic stop on Powell and Smith in the Hollywood area.  As the two officers approached the car, they were kidnapped at gunpoint by the two parolees and forced into Powell's car. They were driven north from Los Angeles to an onion field near Bakersfield, where Officer Campbell was fatally shot.  Officer Hettinger was able to escape.\n\nIn the police investigation that ensued after the incident, the ability of LAPD detectives to get timely and necessary information from the Department of Corrections was severely hampered, ostensibly by the size and bureaucracy of the department. Detectives needed a way to obtain information quickly and have the assistance of the CDCR resources. Because of this tragic incident and the legislative conferences afterward, a decision was made to form the Special Service Unit.\n\nCharles Casey, who was an assistant director with CDCR at the time, learned of a unit within the New York Department of Corrections that seemed to bridge the gap between New York state parole services and local law enforcement. Casey met with Russell H. Oswald, chairman of the New York State Parole Board, who was the founder of the Bureau of Special Services within the New York parole division. Based upon his study and evaluation of the Bureau of Special Services, Casey came back to California and designed a similar unit, calling it the Special Service Unit. After the legislature approved its formation, the unit officially began services in 1964.\n\nThe unit serves as the primary investigative unit for CDCR on cases that stem from the prison or state parolees and affect the street. According to its official description, SSU \"conducts the major criminal investigations and prosecutions, criminal apprehension efforts of prison escapees and parolees wanted for serious and violent felonies, is the primary departmental gang management unit, conducts complex gang-related investigations of inmates and parolees suspected of criminal gang activity, and is the administrative investigative and law enforcement liaison unit.\" In layman's terms, this means the unit does anything asked of it to keep communities safe.\n\n<gallery>\n</gallery>\n\n==High Profile Cases Involving SSU==\nThroughout its fifty-year history, the Special Service Unit has been quietly involved in numerous high-profile cases.  One such example is the Patricia Hearst kidnapping by the Symbionese Liberation Army (SLA) in 1974. The SLA was a radical left-wing organization formed in Soledad Prison by Donald DeFreeze. In 1973 Defreeze escaped from prison and was leading the SLA on the streets when they kidnapped Hearst. The day after Hearst's kidnapping, special agents from the unit's San Francisco office provided police with photographs of suspects who matched the overall description of one of the abductors. Thanks to photographs supplied by SSU, DeFreeze was positively identified as one of Hearst's abductors. That identification led to a lengthy investigation of SLA and its origin behind prison walls.\n\nAnother example is the high-profile murders that shook Los Angeles in the late sixties. The murders were committed by members of Charles Manson's cult and came to be known as Helter Skelter. During the course of the investigation into the cult, SSU special agents were requested by Los Angeles Police to interview Bruce Davis, a Manson follower who had been convicted of the 1969 Gary Hinman murder in Los Angeles. Davis was a Manson devotee whom police were trying to turn as an informant into many of the open murders linked to the Manson Family. \n\nOn January 26, 2001, San Francisco resident Diane Whipple was attacked and killed by two large Presa Canario dogs in the hallway of her apartment building. The dogs, named Bane and Hera, were owned by Whipple's neighbors, Marjorie Knoller and Robert Noel. The dogs' actual owner, Paul Schneider, was a high-ranking member of the Aryan Brotherhood prison gang who was serving a life sentence in Pelican Bay State Prison. The Special Service Unit had been investigating the Aryan Brotherhood and its illegal dog breeding business for several months prior to the death of Whipple. SSU was able to assist local law enforcement during the investigation and prosecution of Knoller and Noel.\n\nIn August 2009, Phillip Garrido was arrested in Antioch, Calif.,  for the kidnapping of Jaycee Dugard. He had kidnapped her eighteen years prior and kept her in captivity. The Hayward (Calif.) police department had interest in Garrido as it related to the 1988 kidnapping of nine-year-old Michaela Garecht.  Special agents from SSU assisted the detectives from the Hayward Police Department in the ensuing investigation. In 2011, they assisted in conducting interviews with Garrido and his wife, Nancy Garrido, who had both been sentenced to state prison in California. \n\nIn August 2014, convicted murderer Scott Landers escaped from the back of a CDCR transport van while on the Interstate 5 freeway just north of Atwater, Calif. Landers had been convicted of the stabbing of a 61-year-old man in Riverside, Calif. and was serving twenty-five years to life. Upon his escape, members of the elite Special Service Unit were called in from across the state to lead the investigation. Within twenty-four hours, the escaped murderer was caught and brought back to CDCR custody.\n\n==Current Structure of SSU==\n\nThe current configuration of the Special Service Unit remains true to its origins\u2014small and mobile. As of 2018, CDCR reports there are only thirty SSU special agents. They are based throughout California in clandestine, off-site locations. Every agent is equipped with tactical and surveillance equipment and is ready to respond anywhere within the state at a moment's notice.\n\nIn 2005, CDCR began to consolidate various divisions and units in an effort to realign its organizational structure. During that time the Office of Correctional Safety (OCS) was created, which serves as the \"special operations division\" for the department. Within the OCS are groups such as the Fugitive Apprehension Team (FAT) and the Emergency Operations Unit (EOU). SSU became a branch of OCS as well, which elevated the training and tactical acumen for all of the special agents. With the merger of the EOU unit with SSU, special agents were responsible for attaining a higher level of tactical firearms proficiency as well as tactical high-risk entry training.\n\nServing as the \"detective unit\" for the Department of Corrections, SSU special agents are responsible for keeping current on the latest investigative techniques and current case law.  Special agents often work hand-in-hand with law enforcement investigators from all branches of government, city, county and federal.  Many SSU agents are assigned to regional task forces throughout California and a handful are cross-designated as federal task force officers with such federal partners as the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA), [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) and the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms]] (BATF).\n\n\n==Issues==\n\n===Prison health care===\n{{See also|Plata v. Brown|Coleman v. Brown}}\n\nThere are at multiple ongoing lawsuits over medical care in the California prison system. ''[[Plata v. Brown]]'' is a federal [[class action]] [[civil rights]] lawsuit alleging unconstitutionally inadequate medical services, and as a result of a [[stipulation]] between the plaintiffs and the state, the court issued an [[injunction]] requiring defendants to provide \"only the minimum level of medical care required under the Eighth Amendment.\" However, three years after approving the stipulation as an order of the court, the court conducted an evidentiary hearing that revealed the continued existence of appalling conditions arising from defendants\u2019 failure to provide adequate medical care to California inmates. As a result, the court ruled in June 2005 and issued an order on October 3, 2005 putting the CDCR's medical health care delivery system in [[receivership]], citing the \"depravity\" of the system.<ref>{{cite news | first= James | last= Sterngold | title= U.S. seizes state prison health care | url= http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2005/07/01/MNGOCDHPP71.DTL | work= San Francisco Chronicle | date= July 5, 2005 | accessdate=December 21, 2007 }}</ref> In February 2006, the judge appointed Robert Sillen to the position<ref>{{cite news | first= Solomon | last= Moore | title= Using Muscle to Improve Health Care for Prisoners | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/27/us/27prisons.html | work= New York Times | date=August 27, 2007 | accessdate=December 21, 2007 }}</ref> and Sillen was replaced by J. Clark Kelso in January 2008.<ref>{{cite web | last = Kagan | first = Racheal | title = CPR PRESS RELEASE: Judge Appoints New Prison Health Care Receiver, 01/23/08 | date = January 23, 2008 | url = http://cprinc.org/docs/press/PR_012308_NewReceiver.pdf | format = pdf | accessdate = February 9, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100926003420/http://cprinc.org/docs/press/PR_012308_NewReceiver.pdf | archivedate = September 26, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n''[[Coleman v. Brown]]'' is a federal [[class action]] [[civil rights]] lawsuit alleging unconstitutionally inadequate mental health care, filed on April 23, 1990. On September 13, 1995 the court found the delivery of mental health care violated the [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], and issued an order for injunctive relief requiring defendants to develop plans to remedy the constitutional violations under the supervision of a [[special master]].\n\nFollowing the Governor's issuance of the State of Emergency Proclamation, the plaintiffs in ''Plata'' and ''Coleman'' filed motions to convene a three-judge court to limit the prison population. On July 23, 2007 both the ''Plata'' and ''Coleman'' courts granted the plaintiff's motions and recommended that the cases be assigned to the same three-judge court.<ref name=\"MooreNYT\"/> The Chief Judge of the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit agreed and, on July 26, 2007, convened the instant three-judge district court pursuant to {{usc|28|2284}}.\n\nAs of 2008\u201309 fiscal year, the state of California spent approximately $16,000 per inmate per year on prison health care.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lao.ca.gov/handouts/crimjust/2010/Correctional_health_care_03_18_10.pdf|title=Overview of Adult Correctional Health Care Spending}}</ref> This amount was by far the largest in the country and more than triple the $4,400 spent per inmate in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bjs.ojp.usdoj.gov/content/pub/pdf/spe01.pdf|title=State Prison Expenditures, 2001}}</ref> The state with the second largest prison population in the country, Texas, spent less than $4,000 per inmate per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://universityofcalifornia.edu/sites/uchealth/2010/05/20/prison-health-update/|title=Prison health update}}</ref>\n\n==Union: California Correctional Peace Officers Association==\n{{Further|California Correctional Peace Officers Association }}\nOfficers of the department are represented by the California Correctional Peace Officers Association (the CCPOA). It was founded in 1957 and its stated goals include the protection and safety of officers, and the advocation of laws, funding and policies to improve work operations and protect public safety. The union has had its controversies over the years, including criticism of its large contributions to former California Governor Gray Davis.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}} Since the [[California recall election, 2003]], the CCPOA has been a vocal critic of Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger.{{Citation needed|date=June 2008}}\n\nIn June 2008, the union came under investigation from both the [[California Office of the Inspector General]] and the CDCR for its role in the hiring of a 21-year-old parolee by [[Minorities In Law Enforcement]], an affiliate of CCPOA.<ref>{{cite news | first= Andy | last= Furillo | title= Chief of CCPOA union, Mike Jimenez defends hiring of parolee | url= http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/1029448.html | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080625105018/http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/1029448.html | archivedate= June 25, 2008 | df= mdy-all }}</ref> Upon conclusion of investigations by both agencies, no wrongdoing was found.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|California}}\n*[[List of law enforcement agencies in California]]\n\n'''National:'''\n*[[List of United States state correction agencies]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/}}\n* [https://govt.westlaw.com/calregs/Browse/Home/California/CaliforniaCodeofRegulations?guid=I090873D0D47311DEBC02831C6D6C108E Crime Prevention and Corrections] in the [[California Code of Regulations]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/*/www.yaca.state.ca.us/ California Youth and Adult Corrections Authority] (Archive)\n* [http://www.ccpoa.org/ California Correctional Peace Officers Association]\n* [http://ca-reentry.org/ California Reentry Program]\n\n{{California State Agencies}}\n{{State prisons in California}}\n{{Incarceration in the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:California Department of Corrections And Rehabilitation}}\n[[Category:Penal system in California]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:State corrections departments of the United States]]\n[[Category:State law enforcement agencies of California|Corrections and Rehabilitation]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Scorpion381", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_Department_of_Corrections_and_Rehabilitation"}
{"title_page": "MLS Cup 2006", "text_new": "{{short description|2006 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title = MLS Cup 2006\n| event = [[MLS Cup]]\n| image = MLS Cup 2006.png\n| imagesize = 140px\n| team1  = [[New England Revolution]]\n| team1score = 1\n| team2 = [[Houston Dynamo]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = Houston wins 4\u20133 on [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]]\n| date = {{Start date|2006|11|12|mf=yes}}\n| stadium = [[FC Dallas Stadium|Pizza Hut Park]]\n| city = [[Frisco, Texas]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Brian Ching]]<br />(Houston Dynamo)\n| referee = [[Jair Marrufo]]\n| attendance = 22,427\n| weather = Sunny, {{convert|61|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|abbr=on}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 2005|2005]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 2007|2007]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2006''' was the 11th edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), and took place on November 12, 2006. It was contested between the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Houston Dynamo]] to decide the champion of the [[2006 Major League Soccer season|2006 season]]. The match was played at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], which had hosted the [[MLS Cup 2005|previous cup]].\n\nBoth teams qualified for the playoffs by placing second in their respective conference during the regular season. New England were appearing in their second consecutive final, while Houston had been formed from the relocated [[San Jose Earthquakes]]. The match was tied 1\u20131 on goals scored 71 seconds apart by [[Taylor Twellman]] and [[Brian Ching]] in [[extra time]]. Houston won 4\u20133 in the first [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in MLS Cup history, with Ching scoring the winning penalty kick and [[Pat Onstad]] saving the follow-up in the fifth round. Houston and New England would stage a rematch in the [[MLS Cup 2007|following cup]], which the Dynamo won in Washington, D.C.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Pizza Hut Park 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|[[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], host venue of MLS Cup 2006]]\n\nThe match was hosted at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], the venue of the [[MLS Cup 2005|previous final]] between the [[New England Revolution]] and [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].<ref name=\"DMN-Frisco\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=February 1, 2006 |title=MLS delivers a tasty order |page=C4 |work=[[Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref> The $80 million stadium was opened in August 6, 2005, and serves primarily as the home of [[FC Dallas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wu |first=Esther |date=August 7, 2005 |title=Hard hats off! Pizza Hut Park opens |page=B1 |work=Dallas Morning News |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/080705dnspometpark.4a872d66.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050910191454/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/080705dnspometpark.4a872d66.html |archivedate=September 10, 2005 |accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref> On January 31, 2006, MLS announced that Pizza Hut Park would repeat as the venue for a second consecutive MLS Cup, following a successful bid from FC Dallas; the other bidding finalist was the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], home to the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref name=\"DMN-Frisco\"/><ref name=\"FWST-Frisco\">{{cite news |last=Xavier Lopez |first=Tobias |date=February 1, 2006 |title=Frisco is MLS' big cheese again |page=D3 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref> The Home Depot Center was also the only other venue to previously host consecutive MLS Cups, having done so in [[MLS Cup 2003|2003]] and [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]].<ref name=\"FWST-Frisco\"/> Pizza Hut Park was considered as a model for Houston's proposed stadium, along with other [[soccer-specific stadium]]s built by the league in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=David |date=November 11, 2006 |title=Dynamo head for Metroplex jewel: Pizza Hut Park |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-head-for-Metroplex-jewel-Pizza-Hut-Park-1860890.php |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> During the run-up to the match, the MLS Cup trophy toured the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]] to promote the league and FC Dallas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nichols |first=Bill |date=November 12, 2006 |title=FC Dallas sets bar for future MLS Cups |page=C1 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2006 Major League Soccer season|2006 season]] was the eleventh in the league's history and was contested by twelve teams in two conferences, divided into the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|east]] and [[Western Conference (MLS)|west]]. Each team played a total of 32 matches in the regular season from April to October, facing teams within their conference four times, and teams outside of their conference two times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=February 9, 2006 |title=1836 open with two home games |page=16 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref><ref name=\"Overview\">{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/ |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018164956/http://www.mlsnet.com/about/ |archivedate=October 18, 2006 |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The playoffs ran from mid-October to November and was contested by the top four teams in each conference.<ref name=\"Overview\"/> It was organized into three rounds: a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away series]] with a winner determined by [[aggregate score]] in the Conference Semifinals, a single-match Conference Final, and the MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-Format\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 2006 was contested by the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Houston Dynamo]], who had both finished second in their respective conferences during the regular season.<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\">{{cite news |date=November 11, 2006 |title=Dynamo, Revolution in MLS Cup '06 |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061111&content_id=78366&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111121137/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061111&content_id=78366&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 }}</ref> The two teams finished within two points of each other in regular season standings and had identical home win\u2013loss\u2013draw records. The 2006 final also marked the first time that neither MLS Cup finalist had won their conference or division, as well as the first time that both finalists had qualified despite losing their first playoffs match. New England and Houston played each other twice during the regular season, trading 1\u20131 draws in May and July.<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Smartschan |first=Adam |date=November 11, 2006 |title=Revs' MLS Cup final foe looks mighty familiar |work=[[The Patriot Ledger]] |location=Quincy, Massachusetts}}</ref>\n\n===New England Revolution===\n[[File:TaylorTwellman 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.6|New England Revolution forward [[Taylor Twellman]], who scored two goals in the team's playoff run]]\n\nThe New England Revolution finished as MLS Cup runners-up in [[MLS Cup 2002|2002]] and [[MLS Cup 2005|2005]], losing both championships to the Los Angeles Galaxy in overtime.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\">{{cite web |title=New England Revolution History, 1996\u20132007 |url=http://archive.revolutionsoccer.net/history/ |publisher=New England Revolution |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The Revolution had also qualified for four straight Eastern Conference Finals, losing in 2003 to the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] and in 2004 to [[D.C. United]] in a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in between their MLS Cup appearances.<ref name=\"FW-Revs\">{{cite news |last=Xavier Lopez |first=Tobias |date=November 10, 2006 |title=Revolution seeks to overturn past |page=D3 |work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 7, 2004 |title=In a Thriller, United Prevails |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A31291-2004Nov6.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The team finished second overall in league standings at the end of the 2005 regular season, setting new team records for wins and points after going on an eleven-match unbeaten streak. The Revolution were in their sixth season under manager [[Steve Nicol]], who primarily used a [[3-5-2|3\u20135\u20132 formation]], and kept their starting lineup from the previous season. The team added forwards [[Kyle Brown (soccer)|Kyle Brown]] and [[Willie Sims (footballer)|Willie Sims]] in the offseason to provide additional depth.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchell |first=Shawn |date=March 31, 2006 |title=Eastern Conference Previews |page=F9 |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=March 31, 2006 |title=Revolution have score to settle |page=D2 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27655652/revolution_have_score_to_settle/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe Revolution opened their season with only three wins in their first thirteen matches, including a run of five draws in six matches during a winless streak from May to June.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shinzawa |first=Fluto |date=June 29, 2006 |title=Revolution get points |page=C10 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The team's struggles were blamed, in part, on injuries and [[Clint Dempsey]]'s call-up to play in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] that required manager Steve Nicol to use different starting lineups to rotate players.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Shinzawa |first=Fluto |date=June 28, 2006 |title=With US team's defeat, Revolution wind up a winner |page=C8 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The return of Dempsey and other injured players helped the team to earn three more wins by early July, which helped New England rise from fourth to second in the Eastern Conference standings behind D.C. United.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shinzawa |first=Fluto |date=July 10, 2006 |title=Many happy returns |page=E2 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nDespite a six-match winless run in July and August, blamed on long road trips in the schedule, the Revolution remained in second place but fell further behind D.C. in the conference standings.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=August 9, 2006 |title=Parkhurst back on fast track |page=C8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692135/parkhurst_back_on_fast_track/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=August 28, 2006 |title=For Revolution, ugly does it |page=E2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692170/for_revolution_ugly_does_it/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> New England finished the season with several home matches on a seven-match unbeaten streak, including five wins, which mirrored the end of the previous season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 16, 2006 |title=Revolution finishing fast\u2014once again |page=E3 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27654918/revolution_finishing_fast/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The team finished the regular season with 48 points, their second-highest record, and clinched the second seed in the Eastern Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 15, 2006 |title=Revolution win finale |page=D2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692254/revolution_win_finale/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Dempsey was named to the [[MLS Best XI]], while [[Matt Reis]] and [[Steve Ralston]] finished as finalists for other league awards.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 13, 2006 |title=For five, loss is a third downer |page=D2  |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nNew England was matched against the third-place Chicago Fire in the Eastern Conference Finals, losing 1\u20130 in the first leg away from home and conceding an early goal in the second leg to create a 0\u20132 defect on aggregate.<ref name=\"CHI\">{{cite news |last=Arroyave |first=Luis |date=October 29, 2006 |title=Nightmare of an ending in New England |page=12 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2006-10-29-0610290395-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The Revolution rallied in the second leg with goals by [[Taylor Twellman]] and [[Pat Noonan]] to tie 2\u20132 on aggregate and force a penalty shootout against the Fire, despite missing midfielders Dempsey and [[Shalrie Joseph]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 29, 2006 |title=Revolution put out Fire |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692549/revolution_put_out_fire/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> New England won the shootout 4\u20132 in four rounds, with two saves by goalkeeper Matt Reis (who also scored) to clinch a fifth consecutive appearance in the Eastern Conference Final.<ref name=\"CHI\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Monique |date=October 29, 2006 |title=An honorable effort by Reis |page=2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692656/an_honorable_effort_by_reis/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution mirrored their performance in the 2005 Eastern Conference Final against league winners D.C. United by winning 1\u20130 on a volleyed goal scored in the fourth minute by Twellman. The win clinched an MLS Cup appearance for New England for the third time in five years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 6, 2006 |title=Texas two-step for Revolution |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692904/texas_twostep_for_revolution/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"HOU-Davis\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Chasing a Crown: MLS Cup analysis from Glenn Davis |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/MLS-Cup-analysis-from-Glenn-Davis-1910026.php |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Houston Dynamo===\n{{see also|2006 Houston Dynamo season}}\n[[File:PaulDalglish 2006 MLS Cup trophy.jpg|upright=0.8|thumb|right|[[Paul Dalglish]], who scored two goals in the Western Conference Final, holding the MLS Cup trophy]]\n\nThe Houston Dynamo were formed after owners [[Anschutz Entertainment Group]] announced that the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] would relocate to Houston for the 2006 season, citing a failure to secure a stadium and local ownership group in the Bay Area.<ref>{{cite news |last=FitzGerald |first=Tom |date=December 16, 2005 |title=Seismic shift: Quakes to Houston |page=D1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Seismic-shift-Quakes-to-Houston-2573124.php |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes had won the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]] and [[MLS Cup 2003|2003]] and finished the 2005 season as [[Supporters' Shield]] winners before being eliminated by the Los Angeles Galaxy in the first round of the playoffs.<ref name=\"HOU-05\">{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=December 16, 2005 |title=MLS brings f\u00fatbol to Houston |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/MLS-brings-f-tbol-to-Houston-1915873.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=December 16, 2005 |title=MLS gains Texas rivalry as San Jose moves to Houston |page=C8 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref> The team's players, head coach [[Dominic Kinnear]], and technical staff were transferred to Houston, while the Earthquakes name was retained by the league for an [[expansion team]] that was announced in 2007.<ref name=\"HOU-05\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=FitzGerald |first=Tom |date=July 18, 2007 |title=Soccer aftershock: Quakes coming back |page=D1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Soccer-aftershock-Quakes-coming-back-2580812.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe team was renamed from Houston 1836 to the Dynamo prior to starting the season after objections from the area's Hispanic communities over its reference to the year [[1836]], which marked both the city's founding and Texas's independence from Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=March 7, 2006 |title=Goodbye 1836, hello Dynamo |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Goodbye-1836-hello-Houston-Dynamo-1634753.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> The Dynamo lost only three of their first eighteen matches, including a ten-match unbeaten streak that lasted from May to late July, and only trailed in-state rivals FC Dallas in the Western Conference standings.<ref>{{cite news |last=Byler |first=Brad |date=July 27, 2006 |title=Dynamo fall to Rapids |page=3 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-s-winning-streak-over-1890200.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> Prior to the unbeaten run, Houston were without starting forward [[Brian Ching]], who was called up to the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. national team]] at the World Cup and missed six league matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=July 18, 2006 |title=Ching earns All-Star invite |page=8 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-s-Ching-earns-All-Star-invite-1852419.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> He later missed five more matches due to knee surgery in August,<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\"/> leaving the team without their top goalscorer as it lost against several Western Conference rivals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 12, 2006 |title=Dynamo need scoring jolt |page=3 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 14, 2006 |title=Ching out for about a month |page=13 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Ching-to-miss-about-a-month-1488779.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTo mitigate the loss of Ching, the Dynamo signed Scottish striker [[Paul Dalglish]] and relied more heavily on attacking midfielder [[Dwayne De Rosario]], who recorded ten goals and five assists by late September.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 18, 2006 |title=Dynamo acquire Dalglish |page=10 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=September 17, 2006 |title=Midfielder De Rosario playing like he's Europe-bound |page=4 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/ON-SOCCER-Europe-ahead-for-De-Rosario-1859112.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> After a four-match winless streak in September, which still left the Dynamo in second place,<ref>{{cite news |last=D'Hippolito |first=Joseph |date=September 11, 2006 |title=De Rosario's goal sinks Galaxy |page=11 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> Houston went unbeaten in their remaining six league matches (with two wins) to secure a playoff berth, with 46 points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Edward |first=James |date=October 17, 2006 |title=MLS postseason promises excitement |page=D7 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/650199331/MLS-postseason-promises-excitement.html |work=[[Deseret News]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HC-Chivas\">{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=October 22, 2006 |title=Getting to the playoffs isn't enough for the Dynamo |page=1 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> The team also made it to the semifinals of the [[2006 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]], where they were eliminated by the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |last=D'Hippolito |first=Joseph |date=September 7, 2006 |title=Dynamo fall to Galaxy in U.S. Open Cup semi |page=7 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> De Rosario and defensive midfielder [[Ricardo Clark]] were named to the MLS Best XI for their regular season performances.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 13, 2006 |title=De Rosario, Clark honored |page=15 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nHouston played against third-seeded [[Chivas USA]], themselves a first-time playoff team,<ref name=\"HC-Chivas\"/> in the Western Conference Semifinals and lost 2\u20131 in the first leg at the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]]. After conceding twice before halftime, Brian Ching scored for the Dynamo and Dwayne De Rosario took a [[penalty kick]] in the 86th minute that was saved by Chivas goalkeeper [[Brad Guzan]], denying an equalizing goal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 23, 2006 |title=Chivas hits many high notes in 2-1 playoff victory |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/23/sports/sp-chivas23 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> In the second leg at home, Houston took advantage of a [[red card (sports)|red card]] shown to Chivas striker [[Francisco Palencia]] and pushed for a series-equalizing goal, which came in the 64th minute on a penalty kick scored by [[Brad Davis (soccer)|Brad Davis]]. Ching then scored a header in the third minute of [[stoppage time]] to give the Dynamo a 2\u20130 win, clinching the series with an aggregate score of 3\u20132 without going to extra time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=October 30, 2006 |title=Dynamo advance after defeating Chivas USA |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-advance-after-defeating-Chivas-USA-1891827.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 30, 2006 |title=Houston sends off Chivas USA with a 2-0 win |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/30/sports/sp-chivas30 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the Western Conference Final, the Houston Dynamo hosted the [[Colorado Rapids]], who had defeated conference-leading Dallas as the fourth seed and were appearing in their second consecutive conference final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=November 5, 2006 |title=Dynamo have an edge against visiting Rapids |page=2 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> Colorado took an early lead on a fourth-minute penalty kick scored by [[Jovan Kirovski]] that was awarded after a [[Fouls and misconduct (association football)|handball]] by defender [[Adrian Serioux]] in the box. The Dynamo responded with two goals in quick succession by Paul Dalglish: a {{convert|5|yd|m|adj=mid}} shot in the 10th minute and a 21st-minute header on a cross by [[Brian Mullan]]. Mullan added a third goal for Houston in the 71st minute to clinch a 3\u20131 victory and an MLS Cup appearance for the team in their inaugural season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 6, 2006 |title=Dynamo advance to MLS Cup |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-advance-to-MLS-Cup-1489184.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Forbes |first=Brian |date=November 5, 2006 |title=Rapids lose out on MLS final |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2006/11/05/rapids-lose-out-on-mls-final/ |work=[[The Denver Post]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[New England Revolution]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Houston Dynamo]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top|2nd place in [[2006 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|-style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|32||15||7||10||'''55'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|'''[[New England Revolution]]'''\n|32||12||8||12||'''48'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|32||13||11||8||'''47'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[New York Red Bulls]]\n|32||9||11||12||'''39'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|32||10||14||8||'''38'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2006 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2006 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|2nd place in [[2006 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[FC Dallas]]\n|32||16||12||4||'''52'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|'''[[Houston Dynamo]]'''\n|32||11||8||13||'''46'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Chivas USA]]\n|32||10||9||13||'''43'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|32||11||13||8||'''41'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|32||11||15||6||'''39'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2006 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|[[2006 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|2\u20132 {{pso}}\n|{{nowrap|0\u20131 (A)}}\n|{{nowrap|2\u20131 {{pso|4\u20132}} (H)}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Chivas USA]]\n|3\u20132\n|{{nowrap|1\u20132 (A)}}\n|{{nowrap|2\u20130 (H)}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|colspan=3|1\u20130 (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Final\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|colspan=3|3\u20131 (H)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]], earning a [[Nielsen rating]] of 0.8 and an estimated audience of 1.24 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=December 4, 2012 |title=MLS Cup television ratings dip |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/49487/mls-cup-television-ratings-dip.html |work=Soccer America |url-access=subscription |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Paulsen |date=November 24, 2010 |title=Record Low Rating For 2010 MLS Cup |url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2010/11/record-low-rating-for-2010-mls-cup/ |work=[[Sports Media Watch]] |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref> English play-by-play commentary was provided by Boston-based sportscaster [[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]] and [[Color commentator|color analysis]] by [[Eric Wynalda]] and former U.S. men's national team coach [[Bruce Arena]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=David |date=November 10, 2006 |title=TV-Radio Notebook: Wynalda weighs in on MLS Cup matchup |page= |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/barron/article/TV-RADIO-NOTEBOOK-Wynalda-weighs-in-on-MLS-Cup-1910592.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> [[Brandi Chastain]] provided sideline reporting, while [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]] anchored the pre-game and halftime shows. The match was also carried in 96 countries by [[ESPN International]] and its associated networks.<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 9, 2006 |title=MLS Cup 2006 sold out |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061109&content_id=78189&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112061639/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061109&content_id=78189&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 12, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The MLS Cup pregame show featured Dallas-based choral rock group [[The Polyphonic Spree]], and the halftime show was headlined by Los Angeles alternate rock group [[Under the Influence of Giants]].<ref name=\"FW-Revs\"/><ref>{{cite press release |date=November 7, 2006 |title=Under the Influence of Giants highlights MLS Cup 2006 Halftime Show |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061107&content_id=77975&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112061603/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061107&content_id=77975&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 12, 2007 |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Analysis===\n\nIn 14 previous meetings from 2001 to 2006 between the New England Revolution and the Houston Dynamo and their predecessor, the San Jose Earthquakes, the Revolution had lost nine matches and drew five.<ref name=\"HOU-Davis\"/> Injuries to several of New England's starting players, including Clint Dempsey, Steve Ralston, and [[Daniel Hernandez (soccer)|Daniel Hernandez]] led to uncertainty surrounding the team's starting lineup.<ref name=\"HOU-Davis\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Whitehead |first=Johnnie |date=November 9, 2006 |title=Revolution to try again for championship |page=C3 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> The 2006 cup was also considered the last chance for the core players of the Revolution team, as several looked to move to European leagues or retire.<ref>{{cite news |last=Galarcep |first=Ives |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Last shot for Revolution |page=B6 |work=[[Herald News]] |location=Passaic, New Jersey |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27693516/last_shot_for_revolution/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:PatOnstad 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|[[Pat Onstad]] celebrates after stopping the final penalty kick in the shootout]]\n\nSeveral thousand Dynamo fans traveled over {{convert|260|mi|km}} from Houston to Pizza Hut Park for the match in a caravan of buses and hundreds of cars on [[Interstate 45 (Texas)|Interstate 45]] that was organized by [[Jim McIngvale|\"Mattress Mack\" Jim McIngvale]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ogden-Davis |first=Lucas |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Convoy carries Dynamo fans to Cup |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112061639/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061109&content_id=78189&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111185336/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78537&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Borg |first=Simon |date=October 4, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #47 Orange Crush |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/04/top-50-mls-cup-moments-47-orange-crush |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> The fans settled into various sections of the stadium among a sellout crowd of 22,427.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=David |date=November 13, 2006 |title=Dynamo make fans proud by bringing trophy home |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-make-fans-proud-by-bringing-trophy-home-1851828.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Fallas\">{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 13, 2006 |title=MVP Ching helps Dynamo to MLS Cup victory |page=2 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/MVP-Ching-helps-Dynamo-to-MLS-Cup-victory-1859218.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 13, 2006 |title=Houston Outlasts New England, Wins on Penalty Kicks |page= |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/12/AR2006111201097.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> A special silver ball was produced by [[Adidas]] for the match, based on a variant of the 2006 FIFA World Cup ball.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nierman |first=Johnathan |date=November 8, 2006 |title=Special ball to be used at MLS Cup |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061108&content_id=78068&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112060326/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061108&content_id=78068&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 12, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHouston began the match with a 4\u20134\u20132 formation but switched to match New England's 3\u20135\u20132 after losing their share of ball possession late in the first half.<ref name=\"MLS-Defense\">{{cite news |last=Halpin |first=Jason |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Dynamo defense made right moves |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78636&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111073421/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78636&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref> Despite this, the Dynamo had a chance to score in the 20th minute by Brad Davis that hit the goalpost. It was followed up by a header by Taylor Twellman that was saved by goalkeeper [[Pat Onstad]] five minutes later.<ref name=\"BG\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 13, 2006 |title=Revolution are kicking themselves again |page=D1 |url=http://archive.boston.com/sports/articles/2006/11/13/revolution_are_kicking_themselves_again/ |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The Revolution took control of the game and prompted the Dynamo to make their formation switch while relying more on counterattacks. Before halftime, Houston had another chance in the form of a strike from Dwayne De Rosario that was saved by Matt Reis.<ref name=\"Dynomite\">{{cite news |last=Halpin |first=Jason |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Dy-no-mite! Houston wins MLS Cup |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78552&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128174320/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78552&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=November 28, 2006 |accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew England bolstered their attack early in the second half by substituting attacking midfielder [[Khano Smith]] and forward Clint Dempsey, recovering from an ankle injury.<ref name=\"Dynomite\"/> Both teams traded shots after 20 minutes of play, with the Revolution requiring a save from Matt Reis on a rebounded attempt by Brad Davis and Dempsey failing to finish a cross from Pat Noonan.<ref name=\"BG\"/> Near the end of regulation time in the 86th minute, [[Jay Heaps]] headed a ball into the six-yard box towards Taylor Twellman that was cleared away in front of the goal by Brian Ching.<ref name=\"BG\"/>\n\nAfter remaining scoreless through regulation time, the match went into [[extra time]] and remained in a defensive stalemate.<ref name=\"Dynomite\"/> The Dynamo dropped their attacking players into the midfield and defense to resist pressure from the Revolution, who continued to earn opportunities to score but left themselves vulnerable to counterattacks. [[Alejandro Moreno]], who was substituted late in the second half for Paul Dalglish, missed a header from a corner kick in the 95th minute; this was followed three minutes later by a header from Clint Dempsey that was cleared off the goal line by [[Wade Barrett (soccer)|Wade Barrett]].<ref name=\"BG\"/><ref name=\"Dynomite\"/>\n\nThe opening goal of the match was scored in the 113th minute by Taylor Twellman, who received a slip pass from Khano Smith and made a one-touch shot from {{convert|12|yd}} to end New England's 346-minute scoring drought in MLS Cup finals.<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Twellman and several of his teammates ran across the length of the field to celebrate in front of a section with Revolution fans.<ref name=\"BG\"/> Houston responded from kickoff with a forward run and a cross from the right by Brian Mullan to Ching, who headed the ball into the net and tied the match at 1\u20131 only 71 seconds after Twellman's goal.<ref name=\"BG\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=Matt |date=November 17, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #3 Rapid Response |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/11/18/top-50-mls-cup-moments-3-rapid-response |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The match remained tied at the end of extra time, setting up the first [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in MLS Cup history.<ref name=\"Fallas\"/><ref name=\"Dynomite\"/>\n\nThe penalty shootout featured no saves or misses in the first two rounds, with shots scored by Houston's extra time substitutes [[Kelly Gray]] and [[Stuart Holden]], and New England's Shalrie Joseph and goalkeeper Matt Reis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunt |first=Steve |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Little used Dynamo make big impact |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78603&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111073141/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78603&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> Pat Noonan's shot in the third round hit the crossbar, but the score remained level at 3\u20133 after Twellman converted and Brad Davis's penalty was saved by Matt Reis.<ref name=\"BG\"/> Ching, who was later named the MLS Cup MVP, scored the Dynamo's fifth-round penalty to give them a 4\u20133 lead.<ref>{{cite news |last=Falkoff |first=Robert |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Dynamo's Ching named MLS Cup MVP |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78616&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111073214/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78616&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> Defender Jay Heaps attempted to slot his penalty into the goal, but the shot slowly rolled into the gloves of Pat Onstad to win the match for the Houston Dynamo.<ref name=\"Fallas\"/><ref name=\"BG\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n| date         = {{Start date|2006|11|12|mf=y}}\n| time         = 15:30 [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| team1        = [[New England Revolution]]\n| team2        = [[Houston Dynamo]]\n| score        = 1\u20131\n| aet          = yes\n| report       = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2006 Report]\n| goals1       = [[Taylor Twellman|Twellman]] {{goal|113}}\n| goals2       = [[Brian Ching|Ching]] {{goal|114}}\n| penaltyscore = 3\u20134\n| penalties1   = \n* [[Shalrie Joseph|Joseph]] {{pengoal}}\n* [[Matt Reis|Reis]] {{pengoal}}\n* [[Pat Noonan|Noonan]] {{penmiss}}\n* [[Taylor Twellman|Twellman]] {{pengoal}}\n* [[Jay Heaps|Heaps]] {{penmiss}}\n| penalties2   = \n* {{pengoal}} [[Kelly Gray|Gray]]\n* {{pengoal}} [[Stuart Holden|Holden]]\n* {{pengoal}} [[Dwayne De Rosario|De Rosario]]\n* {{penmiss}} [[Brad Davis (soccer)|Davis]]\n* {{pengoal}} [[Brian Ching|Ching]]\n| stadium      = [[Toyota Stadium|Pizza Hut Park]]\n| location     = [[Frisco, Texas]]\n| attendance   = 22,427\n| referee      = [[Jair Marrufo]]\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _REVS_06h\n | pattern_b  = _REVS_06h\n | pattern_ra = _REVS_06h\n | pattern_sh = _REVS_06h\n | pattern_so = _REVS_06h\n | leftarm    = FFFFFF\n | body       = FFFFFF\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = FFFFFF\n | socks      = 000030\n | title      = New England Revolution\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _DYNAMO_06\n | pattern_b  = _DYNAMO_06\n | pattern_ra = _DYNAMO_06\n | pattern_sh = _DYNAMO_06\n | pattern_so = _3_stripes_white\n | leftarm    = FF6F00\n | body       = FF6F00\n | rightarm   = FF6F00\n | shorts     = F2F2F2\n | socks      = FF6F00\n | title      = Houston Dynamo\n}}\n|}\n\n{| style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:50%;\"|\n{| style=\"font-size: 90%\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n|colspan=\"4\"|\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Matt Reis]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jay Heaps]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4'''||{{flagicon|TRI}} [[Avery John]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''15''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Michael Parkhurst]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''25'''||{{flagicon|WAL}} [[Andy Dorman]] || || {{suboff|62}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Joe Franchino]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]]) || {{yel|16}} || {{suboff|53}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''3'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez (soccer)|Daniel Hern\u00e1ndez]] || || {{suboff|111}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''21''' ||{{flagicon|GRN}} [[Shalrie Joseph]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''14''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Ralston]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''11''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Pat Noonan]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''20''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Taylor Twellman]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''12'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Doug Warren]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''16'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[James Riley (soccer)|James Riley]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''31'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Jeff Larentowicz]] || || {{subon|111}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''30'''||{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Abundis]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|URU}} [[Jos\u00e9 Cancela]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''2''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Clint Dempsey]] || || {{subon|62}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''18'''||{{flagicon|BER}} [[Khano Smith]] || || {{subon|53}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Steve Nicol]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|[[File:MLS Cup 2006 Formation.svg|300px]]\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''18''' ||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Pat Onstad]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''16''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Craig Waibel]] || {{yel|103}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''5'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Ryan Cochrane (soccer)|Ryan Cochrane]] || {{yel|99}} || {{suboff|102}}\n|-\n|DF ||'''2'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Eddie Robinson (soccer)|Eddie Robinson]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''24''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Wade Barrett (soccer)|Wade Barrett]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|MF ||'''9'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Mullan]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''14''' ||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Dwayne De Rosario]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''51'''||{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Adrian Serioux]] || || {{suboff|114}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brad Davis (soccer)|Brad Davis]] || {{yel|23}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''25''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Ching]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''8'''||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Paul Dalglish]] || || {{suboff|81}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''1'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Zach Wells]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Aloisi]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''3''' ||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kevin Goldthwaite]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Kelly Gray]] || || {{subon|102}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Stuart Holden]] || || {{subon|114}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''7'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Chris Wondolowski]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|VEN}} [[Alejandro Moreno]] || || {{subon|81}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Dominic Kinnear]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />{{flagicon|USA}} [[Brian Ching]]\n\n'''[[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referees]]:'''\n<br />Craig Lowry (United States)\n<br />Nate Clement (United States)\n<br />'''[[Assistant referee (association football)#Fourth official|Fourth official]]:'''\n<br />[[Kevin Stott]] (United States)\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*30 minutes of [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] if necessary.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still level.\n*Seven named substitutes.\n*Maximum of three substitutions.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe Dynamo's victory in the MLS Cup brought the first professional sports championship to the city since the [[Houston Comets]] won the [[2000 WNBA Finals]]. The team was honored with a victory rally outside [[Houston City Hall]] that was attended by 600 fans a few days after the match.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 15, 2006 |title=Dynamo saluted by city |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Mayor-Dynamo-fans-say-thanks-1874776.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The title was technically the third MLS Cup for the franchise, which had won two as the [[San Jose Earthquakes]], but the two teams are considered separate entities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |date=November 11, 2006 |title=The Quakes, at home in Houston |page=D9 |work=[[The Mercury News]]}}</ref> The Dynamo were also received by President [[George W. Bush]] at the [[White House]] in May 2007, becoming the second MLS team to be honored at the White House.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 24, 2007 |title=White House visit on Dynamo itinerary |page=2 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> The time between the match's two extra time goals, 71 seconds, tied the record for shortest span in MLS Cup history that was set in 2003 by San Jose and Chicago.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 12, 2006 |title=MLS Cup 2006 notebook |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78640&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111185345/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78640&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> New England tied Los Angeles's three MLS Cup losses and was compared to similar perennial runners-up like the [[Buffalo Bills]] and [[Minnesota Vikings]] of the [[National Football League]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Biglin |first=Mike |date=November 14, 2006 |title=Runner-up role too familiar for Revs |page=49 |work=The Boston Herald}}</ref><ref name=\"BG-Loss\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 14, 2006 |title=Latest loss one Revolution feel to their core |page=C9 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27694905/latest_loss_one_revolution_feel_to/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 27, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nAs the winner of the MLS Cup, Houston qualified for the [[2007 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], an eight-team tournament to determine the continental club champion;<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=February 18, 2007 |title=Dynamo get ready for international play |page=2 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/SOCCER-NOTEBOOK-Dynamo-get-ready-for-1794138.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> the second MLS berth that was reserved for the MLS Cup runners-up was replaced with one for the winner of the Supporters' Shield.<ref name=\"BG-Loss\"/> The Dynamo played Costa Rican club [[Puntarenas F.C.]] in the quarterfinal and advanced with a 2\u20131 aggregate score, winning 2\u20130 in the second leg at their preseason home in [[College Station, Texas|College Station]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=March 2, 2007 |title=Dynamo blow past Puntarenas |page=10 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-top-Puntarenas-to-reach-Champions-semis-1813149.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> Houston then faced Mexican Clasura champion [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]] in the semifinals and won the first leg 2\u20130 after a one-day delay due to a [[power outage]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=March 16, 2007 |title=Dynamo shut out Pachuca |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-shut-out-Pachuca-in-opener-1833365.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> In the second leg hosted by Pachuca, the Dynamo conceded four goals to tie the series 4\u20134 and force extra time, where Pachuca scored a winning penalty kick to advance 5\u20134 on aggregate to the final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=April 6, 2007 |title=Overtime goal costs Dynamo series with Pachuca |page=9 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Overtime-goal-costs-Dynamo-series-with-Pachuca-1533774.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe two clubs would meet again in the [[MLS Cup 2007|following final]], playing in the first repeat match-up in MLS Cup history; Houston defeated New England 2\u20131 in regulation time and defended their title.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 19, 2007 |title=Once again, Dynamo return home as champions |page=2 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Once-again-Dynamo-return-home-as-champions-1805482.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2008 North American SuperLiga|2008 SuperLiga Final]], hosted by New England at [[Gillette Stadium]], the two teams drew 2\u20132 after extra time and played in a penalty shootout that the Revolution won 6\u20135 after eight rounds.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Monique |date=August 6, 2008 |title=A super finish for Revolution |page=D2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27703910/a_super_finish_for_revolution/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 27, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 7, 2008 |title=SuperLiga loss still a win for Dynamo |page=2 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/ON-SOCCER-SuperLiga-loss-still-a-win-for-Dynamo-1764065.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> The Dynamo appeared in two more MLS Cup finals, played in [[MLS Cup 2011|2011]] and [[MLS Cup 2012|2012]], losing both to the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] at the Home Depot Center in Carson, California.<ref>{{cite news |last=de Jesus Ortiz |first=Jose |date=December 2, 2012 |title=On the Dynamo: Better effort, but a worse loss |page=6 |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/dynamo/article/On-the-Dynamo-Better-effort-but-a-worse-loss-4084356.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> New England qualified for their fifth MLS Cup final in [[MLS Cup 2014|2014]], also losing to the Galaxy in Carson.<ref>{{cite news |last=Powers |first=John |date=December 8, 2014 |title=Galaxy defeat Revolution for record fifth MLS title |page=B1 |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> Both teams would go on to win the [[U.S. Open Cup]], with New England defeating FC Dallas in [[2007 U.S. Open Cup|2007]] and Houston defeating the [[Philadelphia Union]] in [[2018 U.S. Open Cup|2018]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 4, 2007 |title=Finally, Revolution enjoy slice of glory |page=F1 |url=http://archive.boston.com/sports/articles/2007/10/04/finally_revolution_enjoy_slice_of_glory/ |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Glynn A. |date=September 26, 2018 |title=Dynamo defeat Union to win U.S. Open Cup |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-defeat-Union-to-win-U-S-Open-Cup-13261438.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLS Cup}}\n{{2006 in American soccer}}\n{{Houston Dynamo matches}}\n{{New England Revolution matches}}\n\n[[Category:MLS Cup|2006]]\n[[Category:2006 Major League Soccer season|*]]\n[[Category:Houston Dynamo matches]]\n[[Category:New England Revolution matches]]\n[[Category:Association football penalty shoot-outs]]\n[[Category:November 2006 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2006 in sports in Texas]]\n[[Category:Sports in Frisco, Texas]]\n[[Category:Soccer in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2006 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title = MLS Cup 2006\n| event = [[MLS Cup]]\n| image = MLS Cup 2006.png\n| imagesize = 140px\n| team1  = [[New England Revolution]]\n| team1score = 1\n| team2 = [[Houston Dynamo]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = Houston wins 4\u20133 on [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]]\n| date = {{Start date|2006|11|12|mf=yes}}\n| stadium = [[FC Dallas Stadium|Pizza Hut Park]]\n| city = [[Frisco, Texas]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Brian Ching]]<br />(Houston Dynamo)\n| referee = [[Jair Marrufo]]\n| attendance = 22,427\n| weather = Sunny, {{convert|61|\u00b0F|\u00b0C|abbr=on}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 2005|2005]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 2007|2007]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2006''' was the 11th edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), and took place on November 12, 2006. It was contested between the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Houston Dynamo]] to decide the champion of the [[2006 Major League Soccer season|2006 season]]. The match was played at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], which had hosted the [[MLS Cup 2005|previous cup]].\n\nBoth teams qualified for the playoffs by placing second in their respective conference during the regular season. New England were appearing in their second consecutive final, while Houston had been formed from the relocated [[San Jose Earthquakes]]. The match was tied 1\u20131 on goals scored 71 seconds apart by [[Taylor Twellman]] and [[Brian Ching]] in [[extra time]]. Houston won 4\u20133 in the first [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in MLS Cup history, with Ching scoring the winning penalty kick and [[Pat Onstad]] saving the follow-up in the fifth round. Houston and New England would stage a rematch in the [[MLS Cup 2007|following cup]], which the Dynamo won in Washington, D.C.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Pizza Hut Park 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|[[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], host venue of MLS Cup 2006]]\n\nThe match was hosted at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], the venue of the [[MLS Cup 2005|previous final]] between the [[New England Revolution]] and [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].<ref name=\"DMN-Frisco\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=February 1, 2006 |title=MLS delivers a tasty order |page=C4 |work=[[Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref> The $80 million stadium was opened in August 6, 2005, and serves primarily as the home of [[FC Dallas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wu |first=Esther |date=August 7, 2005 |title=Hard hats off! Pizza Hut Park opens |page=B1 |work=Dallas Morning News |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/080705dnspometpark.4a872d66.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050910191454/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/080705dnspometpark.4a872d66.html |archivedate=September 10, 2005 |accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref> On January 31, 2006, MLS announced that Pizza Hut Park would repeat as the venue for a second consecutive MLS Cup, following a successful bid from FC Dallas; the other bidding finalist was the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]], home to the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref name=\"DMN-Frisco\"/><ref name=\"FWST-Frisco\">{{cite news |last=Xavier Lopez |first=Tobias |date=February 1, 2006 |title=Frisco is MLS' big cheese again |page=D3 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref> The Home Depot Center was also the only other venue to previously host consecutive MLS Cups, having done so in [[MLS Cup 2003|2003]] and [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]].<ref name=\"FWST-Frisco\"/> Pizza Hut Park was considered as a model for Houston's proposed stadium, along with other [[soccer-specific stadium]]s built by the league in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=David |date=November 11, 2006 |title=Dynamo head for Metroplex jewel: Pizza Hut Park |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-head-for-Metroplex-jewel-Pizza-Hut-Park-1860890.php |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> During the run-up to the match, the MLS Cup trophy toured the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]] to promote the league and FC Dallas.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nichols |first=Bill |date=November 12, 2006 |title=FC Dallas sets bar for future MLS Cups |page=C1 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league based in the United States. The [[2006 Major League Soccer season|2006 season]] was the eleventh in the league's history and was contested by twelve teams in two conferences, divided into the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|east]] and [[Western Conference (MLS)|west]]. Each team played a total of 32 matches in the regular season from April to October, facing teams within their conference four times, and teams outside of their conference two times.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=February 9, 2006 |title=1836 open with two home games |page=16 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref><ref name=\"Overview\">{{cite web |title=About Major League Soccer: General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/about/ |publisher=[[Major League Soccer]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018164956/http://www.mlsnet.com/about/ |archivedate=October 18, 2006 |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The playoffs ran from mid-October to November and was contested by the top four teams in each conference.<ref name=\"Overview\"/> It was organized into three rounds: a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away series]] with a winner determined by [[aggregate score]] in the Conference Semifinals, a single-match Conference Final, and the MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-Format\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMLS Cup 2006 was contested by the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Houston Dynamo]], who had both finished second in their respective conferences during the regular season.<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\">{{cite news |date=November 11, 2006 |title=Dynamo, Revolution in MLS Cup '06 |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061111&content_id=78366&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111121137/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061111&content_id=78366&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 }}</ref> The two teams finished within two points of each other in regular season standings and had identical home win\u2013loss\u2013draw records. The 2006 final also marked the first time that neither MLS Cup finalist had won their conference or division, as well as the first time that both finalists had qualified despite losing their first playoffs match. New England and Houston played each other twice during the regular season, trading 1\u20131 draws in May and July.<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Smartschan |first=Adam |date=November 11, 2006 |title=Revs' MLS Cup final foe looks mighty familiar |work=[[The Patriot Ledger]] |location=Quincy, Massachusetts}}</ref>\n\n===New England Revolution===\n[[File:TaylorTwellman 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.6|New England Revolution forward [[Taylor Twellman]], who scored two goals in the team's playoff run]]\n\nThe New England Revolution finished as MLS Cup runners-up in [[MLS Cup 2002|2002]] and [[MLS Cup 2005|2005]], losing both championships to the Los Angeles Galaxy in overtime.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\">{{cite web |title=New England Revolution History, 1996\u20132007 |url=http://archive.revolutionsoccer.net/history/ |publisher=New England Revolution |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The Revolution had also qualified for four straight Eastern Conference Finals, losing in 2003 to the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] and in 2004 to [[D.C. United]] in a [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in between their MLS Cup appearances.<ref name=\"FW-Revs\">{{cite news |last=Xavier Lopez |first=Tobias |date=November 10, 2006 |title=Revolution seeks to overturn past |page=D3 |work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 7, 2004 |title=In a Thriller, United Prevails |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A31291-2004Nov6.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The team finished second overall in league standings at the end of the 2005 regular season, setting new team records for wins and points after going on an eleven-match unbeaten streak. The Revolution were in their sixth season under manager [[Steve Nicol]], who primarily used a [[3-5-2|3\u20135\u20132 formation]], and kept their starting lineup from the previous season. The team added forwards [[Kyle Brown (soccer)|Kyle Brown]] and [[Willie Sims (footballer)|Willie Sims]] in the offseason to provide additional depth.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchell |first=Shawn |date=March 31, 2006 |title=Eastern Conference Previews |page=F9 |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=March 31, 2006 |title=Revolution have score to settle |page=D2 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27655652/revolution_have_score_to_settle/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe Revolution opened their season with only three wins in their first thirteen matches, including a run of five draws in six matches during a winless streak from May to June.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shinzawa |first=Fluto |date=June 29, 2006 |title=Revolution get points |page=C10 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The team's struggles were blamed, in part, on injuries and [[Clint Dempsey]]'s call-up to play in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] that required manager Steve Nicol to use different starting lineups to rotate players.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Shinzawa |first=Fluto |date=June 28, 2006 |title=With US team's defeat, Revolution wind up a winner |page=C8 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The return of Dempsey and other injured players helped the team to earn three more wins by early July, which helped New England rise from fourth to second in the Eastern Conference standings behind D.C. United.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shinzawa |first=Fluto |date=July 10, 2006 |title=Many happy returns |page=E2 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nDespite a six-match winless run in July and August, blamed on long road trips in the schedule, the Revolution remained in second place but fell further behind D.C. in the conference standings.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=August 9, 2006 |title=Parkhurst back on fast track |page=C8 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692135/parkhurst_back_on_fast_track/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=August 28, 2006 |title=For Revolution, ugly does it |page=E2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692170/for_revolution_ugly_does_it/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> New England finished the season with several home matches on a seven-match unbeaten streak, including five wins, which mirrored the end of the previous season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 16, 2006 |title=Revolution finishing fast\u2014once again |page=E3 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27654918/revolution_finishing_fast/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The team finished the regular season with 48 points, their second-highest record, and clinched the second seed in the Eastern Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 15, 2006 |title=Revolution win finale |page=D2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692254/revolution_win_finale/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> Dempsey was named to the [[MLS Best XI]], while [[Matt Reis]] and [[Steve Ralston]] finished as finalists for other league awards.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 13, 2006 |title=For five, loss is a third downer |page=D2  |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nNew England was matched against the third-place Chicago Fire in the Eastern Conference Finals, losing 1\u20130 in the first leg away from home and conceding an early goal in the second leg to create a 0\u20132 defect on aggregate.<ref name=\"CHI\">{{cite news |last=Arroyave |first=Luis |date=October 29, 2006 |title=Nightmare of an ending in New England |page=12 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2006-10-29-0610290395-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The Revolution rallied in the second leg with goals by [[Taylor Twellman]] and [[Pat Noonan]] to tie 2\u20132 on aggregate and force a penalty shootout against the Fire, despite missing midfielders Dempsey and [[Shalrie Joseph]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 29, 2006 |title=Revolution put out Fire |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692549/revolution_put_out_fire/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> New England won the shootout 4\u20132 in four rounds, with two saves by goalkeeper Matt Reis (who also scored) to clinch a fifth consecutive appearance in the Eastern Conference Final.<ref name=\"CHI\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Monique |date=October 29, 2006 |title=An honorable effort by Reis |page=2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692656/an_honorable_effort_by_reis/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution mirrored their performance in the 2005 Eastern Conference Final against league winners D.C. United by winning 1\u20130 on a volleyed goal scored in the fourth minute by Twellman. The win clinched an MLS Cup appearance for New England for the third time in five years.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 6, 2006 |title=Texas two-step for Revolution |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27692904/texas_twostep_for_revolution/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref name=\"HOU-Davis\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Chasing a Crown: MLS Cup analysis from Glenn Davis |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/MLS-Cup-analysis-from-Glenn-Davis-1910026.php |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Houston Dynamo===\n{{see also|2006 Houston Dynamo season}}\n[[File:PaulDalglish 2006 MLS Cup trophy.jpg|upright=0.8|thumb|right|[[Paul Dalglish]], who scored two goals in the Western Conference Final, holding the MLS Cup trophy]]\n\nThe Houston Dynamo were formed after owners [[Anschutz Entertainment Group]] announced that the [[San Jose Earthquakes]] would relocate to Houston for the 2006 season, citing a failure to secure a stadium and local ownership group in the Bay Area.<ref>{{cite news |last=FitzGerald |first=Tom |date=December 16, 2005 |title=Seismic shift: Quakes to Houston |page=D1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Seismic-shift-Quakes-to-Houston-2573124.php |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> The Earthquakes had won the MLS Cup in [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]] and [[MLS Cup 2003|2003]] and finished the 2005 season as [[Supporters' Shield]] winners before being eliminated by the Los Angeles Galaxy in the first round of the playoffs.<ref name=\"HOU-05\">{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=December 16, 2005 |title=MLS brings f\u00fatbol to Houston |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/MLS-brings-f-tbol-to-Houston-1915873.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=December 16, 2005 |title=MLS gains Texas rivalry as San Jose moves to Houston |page=C8 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref> The team's players, head coach [[Dominic Kinnear]], and technical staff were transferred to Houston, while the Earthquakes name was retained by the league for an [[expansion team]] that was announced in 2007.<ref name=\"HOU-05\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=FitzGerald |first=Tom |date=July 18, 2007 |title=Soccer aftershock: Quakes coming back |page=D1 |url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Soccer-aftershock-Quakes-coming-back-2580812.php |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe team was renamed from Houston 1836 to the Dynamo prior to starting the season after objections from the area's Hispanic communities over its reference to the year [[1836]], which marked both the city's founding and Texas's independence from Mexico.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=March 7, 2006 |title=Goodbye 1836, hello Dynamo |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Goodbye-1836-hello-Houston-Dynamo-1634753.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> The Dynamo lost only three of their first eighteen matches, including a ten-match unbeaten streak that lasted from May to late July, and only trailed in-state rivals FC Dallas in the Western Conference standings.<ref>{{cite news |last=Byler |first=Brad |date=July 27, 2006 |title=Dynamo fall to Rapids |page=3 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-s-winning-streak-over-1890200.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> Prior to the unbeaten run, Houston were without starting forward [[Brian Ching]], who was called up to the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. national team]] at the World Cup and missed six league matches.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=July 18, 2006 |title=Ching earns All-Star invite |page=8 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-s-Ching-earns-All-Star-invite-1852419.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref> He later missed five more matches due to knee surgery in August,<ref name=\"MLS-Preview\"/> leaving the team without their top goalscorer as it lost against several Western Conference rivals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 12, 2006 |title=Dynamo need scoring jolt |page=3 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 14, 2006 |title=Ching out for about a month |page=13 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Ching-to-miss-about-a-month-1488779.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTo mitigate the loss of Ching, the Dynamo signed Scottish striker [[Paul Dalglish]] and relied more heavily on attacking midfielder [[Dwayne De Rosario]], who recorded ten goals and five assists by late September.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=August 18, 2006 |title=Dynamo acquire Dalglish |page=10 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=September 17, 2006 |title=Midfielder De Rosario playing like he's Europe-bound |page=4 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/ON-SOCCER-Europe-ahead-for-De-Rosario-1859112.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> After a four-match winless streak in September, which still left the Dynamo in second place,<ref>{{cite news |last=D'Hippolito |first=Joseph |date=September 11, 2006 |title=De Rosario's goal sinks Galaxy |page=11 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> Houston went unbeaten in their remaining six league matches (with two wins) to secure a playoff berth, with 46 points.<ref>{{cite news |last=Edward |first=James |date=October 17, 2006 |title=MLS postseason promises excitement |page=D7 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/650199331/MLS-postseason-promises-excitement.html |work=[[Deseret News]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HC-Chivas\">{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=October 22, 2006 |title=Getting to the playoffs isn't enough for the Dynamo |page=1 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> The team also made it to the semifinals of the [[2006 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]], where they were eliminated by the Los Angeles Galaxy.<ref>{{cite news |last=D'Hippolito |first=Joseph |date=September 7, 2006 |title=Dynamo fall to Galaxy in U.S. Open Cup semi |page=7 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> De Rosario and defensive midfielder [[Ricardo Clark]] were named to the MLS Best XI for their regular season performances.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 13, 2006 |title=De Rosario, Clark honored |page=15 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nHouston played against third-seeded [[Chivas USA]], themselves a first-time playoff team,<ref name=\"HC-Chivas\"/> in the Western Conference Semifinals and lost 2\u20131 in the first leg at the [[Home Depot Center]] in [[Carson, California]]. After conceding twice before halftime, Brian Ching scored for the Dynamo and Dwayne De Rosario took a [[penalty kick]] in the 86th minute that was saved by Chivas goalkeeper [[Brad Guzan]], denying an equalizing goal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 23, 2006 |title=Chivas hits many high notes in 2-1 playoff victory |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/23/sports/sp-chivas23 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> In the second leg at home, Houston took advantage of a [[red card (sports)|red card]] shown to Chivas striker [[Francisco Palencia]] and pushed for a series-equalizing goal, which came in the 64th minute on a penalty kick scored by [[Brad Davis (soccer)|Brad Davis]]. Ching then scored a header in the third minute of [[stoppage time]] to give the Dynamo a 2\u20130 win, clinching the series with an aggregate score of 3\u20132 without going to extra time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=October 30, 2006 |title=Dynamo advance after defeating Chivas USA |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-advance-after-defeating-Chivas-USA-1891827.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 30, 2006 |title=Houston sends off Chivas USA with a 2-0 win |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/oct/30/sports/sp-chivas30 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the Western Conference Final, the Houston Dynamo hosted the [[Colorado Rapids]], who had defeated conference-leading Dallas as the fourth seed and were appearing in their second consecutive conference final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Glenn |date=November 5, 2006 |title=Dynamo have an edge against visiting Rapids |page=2 |work=Houston Chronicle}}</ref> Colorado took an early lead on a fourth-minute penalty kick scored by [[Jovan Kirovski]] that was awarded after a [[Fouls and misconduct (association football)|handball]] by defender [[Adrian Serioux]] in the box. The Dynamo responded with two goals in quick succession by Paul Dalglish: a {{convert|5|yd|m|adj=mid}} shot in the 10th minute and a 21st-minute header on a cross by [[Brian Mullan]]. Mullan added a third goal for Houston in the 71st minute to clinch a 3\u20131 victory and an MLS Cup appearance for the team in their inaugural season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 6, 2006 |title=Dynamo advance to MLS Cup |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-advance-to-MLS-Cup-1489184.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Forbes |first=Brian |date=November 5, 2006 |title=Rapids lose out on MLS final |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2006/11/05/rapids-lose-out-on-mls-final/ |work=[[The Denver Post]] |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[New England Revolution]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Houston Dynamo]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top|2nd place in [[2006 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|-style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|32||15||7||10||'''55'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|'''[[New England Revolution]]'''\n|32||12||8||12||'''48'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|32||13||11||8||'''47'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[New York Red Bulls]]\n|32||9||11||12||'''39'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|32||10||14||8||'''38'''\n|}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2006 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|2nd place in [[2006 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[FC Dallas]]\n|32||16||12||4||'''52'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|'''[[Houston Dynamo]]'''\n|32||11||8||13||'''46'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Chivas USA]]\n|32||10||9||13||'''43'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|32||11||13||8||'''41'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|32||11||15||6||'''39'''\n|}\n\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|[[2006 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|2\u20132 {{pso}}\n|{{nowrap|0\u20131 (A)}}\n|{{nowrap|2\u20131 {{pso|4\u20132}} (H)}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[Chivas USA]]\n|3\u20132\n|{{nowrap|1\u20132 (A)}}\n|{{nowrap|2\u20130 (H)}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|colspan=3|1\u20130 (A)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Final\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|colspan=3|3\u20131 (H)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]], earning a [[Nielsen rating]] of 0.8 and an estimated audience of 1.24 million.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kennedy |first=Paul |date=December 4, 2012 |title=MLS Cup television ratings dip |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/49487/mls-cup-television-ratings-dip.html |work=Soccer America |url-access=subscription |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Paulsen |date=November 24, 2010 |title=Record Low Rating For 2010 MLS Cup |url=http://www.sportsmediawatch.com/2010/11/record-low-rating-for-2010-mls-cup/ |work=[[Sports Media Watch]] |accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref> English play-by-play commentary was provided by Boston-based sportscaster [[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]] and [[Color commentator|color analysis]] by [[Eric Wynalda]] and former U.S. men's national team coach [[Bruce Arena]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=David |date=November 10, 2006 |title=TV-Radio Notebook: Wynalda weighs in on MLS Cup matchup |page= |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/barron/article/TV-RADIO-NOTEBOOK-Wynalda-weighs-in-on-MLS-Cup-1910592.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> [[Brandi Chastain]] provided sideline reporting, while [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]] anchored the pre-game and halftime shows. The match was also carried in 96 countries by [[ESPN International]] and its associated networks.<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 9, 2006 |title=MLS Cup 2006 sold out |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061109&content_id=78189&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112061639/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061109&content_id=78189&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 12, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The MLS Cup pregame show featured Dallas-based choral rock group [[The Polyphonic Spree]], and the halftime show was headlined by Los Angeles alternate rock group [[Under the Influence of Giants]].<ref name=\"FW-Revs\"/><ref>{{cite press release |date=November 7, 2006 |title=Under the Influence of Giants highlights MLS Cup 2006 Halftime Show |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061107&content_id=77975&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112061603/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061107&content_id=77975&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 12, 2007 |accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Analysis===\n\nIn 14 previous meetings from 2001 to 2006 between the New England Revolution and the Houston Dynamo and their predecessor, the San Jose Earthquakes, the Revolution had lost nine matches and drew five.<ref name=\"HOU-Davis\"/> Injuries to several of New England's starting players, including Clint Dempsey, Steve Ralston, and [[Daniel Hernandez (soccer)|Daniel Hernandez]] led to uncertainty surrounding the team's starting lineup.<ref name=\"HOU-Davis\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Whitehead |first=Johnnie |date=November 9, 2006 |title=Revolution to try again for championship |page=C3 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> The 2006 cup was also considered the last chance for the core players of the Revolution team, as several looked to move to European leagues or retire.<ref>{{cite news |last=Galarcep |first=Ives |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Last shot for Revolution |page=B6 |work=[[Herald News]] |location=Passaic, New Jersey |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27693516/last_shot_for_revolution/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n===Summary===\n[[File:PatOnstad 2006 MLS Cup.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.8|[[Pat Onstad]] celebrates after stopping the final penalty kick in the shootout]]\n\nSeveral thousand Dynamo fans traveled over {{convert|260|mi|km}} from Houston to Pizza Hut Park for the match in a caravan of buses and hundreds of cars on [[Interstate 45 (Texas)|Interstate 45]] that was organized by [[Jim McIngvale|\"Mattress Mack\" Jim McIngvale]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Ogden-Davis |first=Lucas |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Convoy carries Dynamo fans to Cup |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112061639/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061109&content_id=78189&vkey=mlscuppr2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111185336/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78537&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Borg |first=Simon |date=October 4, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #47 Orange Crush |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/10/04/top-50-mls-cup-moments-47-orange-crush |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref> The fans settled into various sections of the stadium among a sellout crowd of 22,427.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barron |first=David |date=November 13, 2006 |title=Dynamo make fans proud by bringing trophy home |page=1 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Dynamo-make-fans-proud-by-bringing-trophy-home-1851828.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Fallas\">{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 13, 2006 |title=MVP Ching helps Dynamo to MLS Cup victory |page=2 |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/MVP-Ching-helps-Dynamo-to-MLS-Cup-victory-1859218.php |work=Houston Chronicle |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Goff\">{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 13, 2006 |title=Houston Outlasts New England, Wins on Penalty Kicks |page= |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/12/AR2006111201097.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> A special silver ball was produced by [[Adidas]] for the match, based on a variant of the 2006 FIFA World Cup ball.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nierman |first=Johnathan |date=November 8, 2006 |title=Special ball to be used at MLS Cup |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061108&content_id=78068&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112060326/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061108&content_id=78068&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 12, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHouston began the match with a 4\u20134\u20132 formation but switched to match New England's 3\u20135\u20132 after losing their share of ball possession late in the first half.<ref name=\"MLS-Defense\">{{cite news |last=Halpin |first=Jason |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Dynamo defense made right moves |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78636&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111073421/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78636&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref> Despite this, the Dynamo had a chance to score in the 20th minute by Brad Davis that hit the goalpost. It was followed up by a header by Taylor Twellman that was saved by goalkeeper [[Pat Onstad]] five minutes later.<ref name=\"BG\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 13, 2006 |title=Revolution are kicking themselves again |page=D1 |url=http://archive.boston.com/sports/articles/2006/11/13/revolution_are_kicking_themselves_again/ |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The Revolution took control of the game and prompted the Dynamo to make their formation switch while relying more on counterattacks. Before halftime, Houston had another chance in the form of a strike from Dwayne De Rosario that was saved by Matt Reis.<ref name=\"Dynomite\">{{cite news |last=Halpin |first=Jason |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Dy-no-mite! Houston wins MLS Cup |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78552&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128174320/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78552&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=November 28, 2006 |accessdate=February 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew England bolstered their attack early in the second half by substituting attacking midfielder [[Khano Smith]] and forward Clint Dempsey, recovering from an ankle injury.<ref name=\"Dynomite\"/> Both teams traded shots after 20 minutes of play, with the Revolution requiring a save from Matt Reis on a rebounded attempt by Brad Davis and Dempsey failing to finish a cross from Pat Noonan.<ref name=\"BG\"/> Near the end of regulation time in the 86th minute, [[Jay Heaps]] headed a ball into the six-yard box towards Taylor Twellman that was cleared away in front of the goal by Brian Ching.<ref name=\"BG\"/>\n\nAfter remaining scoreless through regulation time, the match went into [[extra time]] and remained in a defensive stalemate.<ref name=\"Dynomite\"/> The Dynamo dropped their attacking players into the midfield and defense to resist pressure from the Revolution, who continued to earn opportunities to score but left themselves vulnerable to counterattacks. [[Alejandro Moreno]], who was substituted late in the second half for Paul Dalglish, missed a header from a corner kick in the 95th minute; this was followed three minutes later by a header from Clint Dempsey that was cleared off the goal line by [[Wade Barrett (soccer)|Wade Barrett]].<ref name=\"BG\"/><ref name=\"Dynomite\"/>\n\nThe opening goal of the match was scored in the 113th minute by Taylor Twellman, who received a slip pass from Khano Smith and made a one-touch shot from {{convert|12|yd}} to end New England's 346-minute scoring drought in MLS Cup finals.<ref name=\"Goff\"/> Twellman and several of his teammates ran across the length of the field to celebrate in front of a section with Revolution fans.<ref name=\"BG\"/> Houston responded from kickoff with a forward run and a cross from the right by Brian Mullan to Ching, who headed the ball into the net and tied the match at 1\u20131 only 71 seconds after Twellman's goal.<ref name=\"BG\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=Matt |date=November 17, 2011 |title=Top 50 MLS Cup Moments: #3 Rapid Response |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2011/11/18/top-50-mls-cup-moments-3-rapid-response |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> The match remained tied at the end of extra time, setting up the first [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in MLS Cup history.<ref name=\"Fallas\"/><ref name=\"Dynomite\"/>\n\nThe penalty shootout featured no saves or misses in the first two rounds, with shots scored by Houston's extra time substitutes [[Kelly Gray]] and [[Stuart Holden]], and New England's Shalrie Joseph and goalkeeper Matt Reis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hunt |first=Steve |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Little used Dynamo make big impact |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78603&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111073141/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78603&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref> Pat Noonan's shot in the third round hit the crossbar, but the score remained level at 3\u20133 after Twellman converted and Brad Davis's penalty was saved by Matt Reis.<ref name=\"BG\"/> Ching, who was later named the MLS Cup MVP, scored the Dynamo's fifth-round penalty to give them a 4\u20133 lead.<ref>{{cite news |last=Falkoff |first=Robert |date=November 12, 2006 |title=Dynamo's Ching named MLS Cup MVP |url=http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78616&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111073214/http://web.mlsnet.com/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20061112&content_id=78616&vkey=mlscup2006&fext=.jsp |archivedate=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref> Defender Jay Heaps attempted to slot his penalty into the goal, but the shot slowly rolled into the gloves of Pat Onstad to win the match for the Houston Dynamo.<ref name=\"Fallas\"/><ref name=\"BG\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n| date         = {{Start date|2006|11|12|mf=y}}\n| time         = 15:30 [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| team1        = [[New England Revolution]]\n| team2        = [[Houston Dynamo]]\n| score        = 1\u20131\n| aet          = yes\n| report       = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2006 Report]\n| goals1       = [[Taylor Twellman|Twellman]] {{goal|113}}\n| goals2       = [[Brian Ching|Ching]] {{goal|114}}\n| penaltyscore = 3\u20134\n| penalties1   = \n* [[Shalrie Joseph|Joseph]] {{pengoal}}\n* [[Matt Reis|Reis]] {{pengoal}}\n* [[Pat 