{"title_page": "MLS Cup 2005", "text_new": "{{short description|2005 edition of the MLS Cup}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title = MLS Cup 2005\n| event = [[MLS Cup]]\n| image = MLS Cup 2005.png\n| imagesize = 120px\n| team1 = [[New England Revolution]]\n| team1score = 0\n| team2 = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n| team2score = 1\n| details = After [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]]\n| date = {{Start date|2005|11|13|mf=yes}}\n| stadium = [[FC Dallas Stadium|Pizza Hut Park]]\n| city = [[Frisco, Texas]], US\n| man_of_the_match1a = [[Guillermo Ram\u00edrez]]<br />(Los Angeles Galaxy)\n| referee = [[Kevin Stott]]\n| attendance = 21,193\n| weather = Sunny, {{convert|75|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}\n| previous = [[MLS Cup 2004|2004]]\n| next = [[MLS Cup 2006|2006]]\n}}\n\n'''MLS Cup 2005''' was the 10th edition of the [[MLS Cup]], the championship match of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS). The match took place on November 13, 2005, at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], near [[Dallas]], and was contested between the [[New England Revolution]] and the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]. It was a rematch of [[MLS Cup 2002]] and ended in a repeat victory for Los Angeles, who won 1\u20130 on a goal scored by [[Guillermo Ram\u00edrez]] in [[extra time]].\n\nNew England qualified as the top seed in the [[Eastern Conference (MLS)|Eastern Conference]] with several players named to the [[MLS Best XI]], while Los Angeles was the lowest-seeded playoff team and had rebuilt its roster in the offseason. Ram\u00edrez, who was brought in on [[loan (sports)|loan]] from [[CSD Municipal]], had scored no goals from open play despite 62 shots but was substituted into the MLS Cup final and scored the winning goal.\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Pizza Hut Park - FC Dallas vs. DC United, 2010 (4778604007).jpg|thumb|left|MLS Cup 2005 was hosted at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], home to [[FC Dallas]].]]\n\nThe match was hosted at [[Pizza Hut Park]] in [[Frisco, Texas]], the newly-built home of [[FC Dallas]]. The 21,000-seat stadium was announced as the host on November 12, 2004.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=November 13, 2004 |title=Frisco's new stadium will play host to '05 MLS Cup |page=C6 |work=[[Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref> It was the third major [[soccer-specific stadium]] to be built for an MLS team and cost $80 million to construct, opening on August 6, 2005.<ref>{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=February 8, 2005 |title=MLS final still set for Frisco |page=C3 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Wu |first=Esther |date=August 7, 2005 |title=Hard hats off! Pizza Hut Park opens |page=B1 |work=Dallas Morning News |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/080705dnspometpark.4a872d66.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050910191454/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/080705dnspometpark.4a872d66.html |archivedate=September 10, 2005 |accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The stadium sits at the center of a {{convert|145|acre|ha|adj=mid}} complex with 17 soccer fields located near downtown Frisco, approximately {{convert|30|mi|km}} north of [[Downtown Dallas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Galarcep |first=Ives |date=August 9, 2005 |title=Dallas stadium Metros' model |page=D1 |work=[[Herald News]] |location=Passaic, New Jersey |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27304873/dallas_stadium_metros_model/ |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117123901/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27304873/dallas_stadium_metros_model/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=December 11, 2014 |title=U.S. Soccer Hall of Fame in suburban Dallas? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2014/12/11/u-s-soccer-hall-of-fame-in-suburban-dallas/?noredirect=on |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117122324/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2014/12/11/u-s-soccer-hall-of-fame-in-suburban-dallas/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.bb0401e29410 |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prior to the match, the league hosted pre-game festivities at nearby venues and parking lots, including events with FC Dallas players.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nierman |first=Johnathan |date=November 13, 2005 |title=Fans warm up at Soccer Celebration |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48223&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060521184544/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48223&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |archivedate=May 21, 2006 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> Pizza Hut Park (later renamed Toyota Stadium) would go on to host [[MLS Cup 2006]], and the [[2007 U.S. Open Cup Final|2007]] and [[2016 U.S. Open Cup Final|2016]] finals of the [[U.S. Open Cup]], which all featured the [[New England Revolution]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 2, 2007 |title=Revolution hope Dallas episode isn't a rerun |page=D12 |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27558233/revolution_hope_dallas_episode_isnt_a/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 23, 2019}} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=McFarland |first=Shawn |date=September 13, 2016 |title=Revolution eye US Open Cup title |page=D4 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2016/09/12/revolution-eye-open-cup-crown/odu4dvBwkES0TwEpCftl3N/story.html |accessdate=January 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714002516/https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2016/09/12/revolution-eye-open-cup-crown/odu4dvBwkES0TwEpCftl3N/story.html |archive-date=July 14, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{main|2005 MLS Cup Playoffs}}\n\nThe [[MLS Cup]] is the post-season championship of [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), a professional club soccer league in the United States. The [[2005 Major League Soccer season|2005 season]] was the tenth in league history, and was contested by twelve teams divided into two conferences. Each club played 32 matches during the regular season from April 2 to October 16, facing each team twice and in-conference teams two additional times.<ref>{{cite press release |date=February 14, 2005 |title=MLS releases 2005 schedule |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_news.jsp?ymd=20050214&content_id=22276&vkey=pr_mls&fext=.jsp |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312080707/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_news.jsp?ymd=20050214&content_id=22276&vkey=pr_mls&fext=.jsp |archivedate=March 12, 2005 |accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> The playoffs, running from October 21 to November 13, were contested by the top four clubs in each conference.<ref>{{cite web |title=General Overview |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/about/ |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507154544/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/about/ |archivedate=May 7, 2005 |accessdate=January 9, 2019}}</ref> It was organized into three rounds: a [[two-legged tie|home-and-away series]] in the Conference Semifinals, a single-match Conference Final, and the MLS Cup final.<ref name=\"MLS-Format\">{{cite news |last=Rodriguez |first=Alicia |date=October 21, 2015 |title=Audi MLS Cup Playoffs: Tracing the evolution of the postseason format since 1996 |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |work=MLSsoccer.com |accessdate=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113165913/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2015/10/21/audi-mls-cup-playoffs-tracing-evolution-postseason-format |archive-date=November 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe tenth MLS Cup was contested between the [[New England Revolution]] and [[Los Angeles Galaxy]] in a rematch of the [[MLS Cup 2002|2002 final]], which the Galaxy won 1\u20130.<ref name=\"Tribune-Preview\">{{cite news |last=Arroyave |first=Luis |date=November 13, 2005 |title=Strangers? Not in this title match |page=3 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-11-13-0511120309-story.html |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110074025/https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-11-13-0511120309-story.html |archive-date=January 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was the second time that an MLS Cup final featured a previous matchup. New England finished the regular season atop the Eastern Conference, while Los Angeles was the lowest-ever seed to play in the MLS Cup final after finishing eighth overall.<ref>{{cite news |last=Green |first=Nick |date=November 8, 2005 |title=Galaxy peaks at the right time, with another MLS Cup in sight |page=D6 |work=[[Daily Breeze]] |location=Torrance, California}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fallas |first=Bernardo |date=November 14, 2005 |title=Galaxy capture second MLS Cup |page=1 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/dynamo/article/Sub-s-goal-captures-second-MLS-Cup-for-Galaxy-1938662.php |accessdate=January 23, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy and Revolution played twice in the regular season and both matches ended in 1\u20131 draws.<ref>{{cite web |title=2005 Results |url=https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/history/results/2005 |publisher=New England Revolution |accessdate=January 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190110133759/https://www.revolutionsoccer.net/history/results/2005 |archive-date=January 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===New England Revolution===\n\nNew England Revolution made it to two consecutive Eastern Conference finals in 2003 and 2004 under head coach [[Steve Nicol]], who was promoted from his interim role during the run to the 2002 final. The club drafted several young midfielders and forwards during the two seasons, including [[Pat Noonan]], [[Shalrie Joseph]], and [[Clint Dempsey]], who helped replace retiring players or injured starters.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\">{{cite web |title=New England Revolution History, 1996\u20132007 |url=http://archive.revolutionsoccer.net/history/ |publisher=New England Revolution |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116150047/http://archive.revolutionsoccer.net/history/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Dempsey was named [[MLS Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] for his performance in the 2004 season, scoring seven goals and finishing third on the team in scoring behind Noonan and [[Taylor Twellman]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Galarcep |first=Ives |date=November 2, 2004 |title=New year, same end for Metros |page=C1 |work=Herald News |location=Passaic, New Jersey}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Pukalo |first=Mark |date=July 16, 2005 |title=Dempsey making a mark |page=C4 |url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2005-07-16-0507160580-story.html |work=[[Hartford Courant]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116150439/https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-2005-07-16-0507160580-story.html |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Revolution finished tied with the [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]] for the worst record in the league in 2004 and qualified for the playoffs on the last day of the regular season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 17, 2004 |title=Revolution in with the in crowd |page=F1 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The team then defeated the [[Supporters' Shield]]-winning [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]] 2\u20131 on [[aggregate score|aggregate]] in the Conference Semifinals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 1, 2004 |title=Stops help Revolution go |page=D1 |url=http://archive.boston.com/sports/articles/2004/11/01/stops_help_revolution_go/ |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116200802/http://archive.boston.com/sports/articles/2004/11/01/stops_help_revolution_go/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> They advanced to the Conference Final, drawing 3\u20133 with [[D.C. United]] after [[extra time]] and losing 4\u20133 in the resulting [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]] in the sudden death sixth round.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=November 7, 2004 |title=In a Thriller, United Prevails |page=E1 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A31291-2004Nov6.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116200716/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A31291-2004Nov6.html |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Revolution opened the 2005 season with an eleven-match unbeaten streak, including six consecutive wins, that propelled them to first place in the Eastern Conference.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=June 19, 2005 |title=Revolution stopped at start |page=C2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274562/revolution_stopped_at_start/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116150035/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274562/revolution_stopped_at_start/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> The team, however, lost its place atop the conference to Chicago by July due to key players being released for national team callups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Kelsie |date=July 17, 2005 |title=Late heroics by Twellman beat Dallas |page=C3 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274573/late_heroics_by_twellman_beat_dallas/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116150049/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274573/late_heroics_by_twellman_beat_dallas/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> New England then regained its first-place spot, but lost several players in early August to injuries after playing five league and [[U.S. Open Cup]] matches in 15 days.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=August 19, 2005 |title=Revolution get chance to put their feet up |page=E3 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274592/revolution_get_chance_to_put_their_feet/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116150128/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274592/revolution_get_chance_to_put_their_feet/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution finished the regular season with only two losses in their last nine matches, completing their best-ever season record. New England finished second in [[Supporters' Shield]] standings behind [[San Jose Earthquakes|San Jose]], but set new team records for wins, with 17, and a conference record for points, with 59.<ref name=\"RevsHistory\"/><ref name=\"USA-ECF\">{{cite news |last=Dure |first=Beau |date=November 3, 2005 |title=New England aims to stop MLS upset trend |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/mls/2005-11-03-east-preview_x.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 17, 2005 |title=Style points for Revolution |page=D2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274630/style_points_for_revolution/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116200744/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274630/style_points_for_revolution/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> Twellman's 17 goals earned him the [[MLS Golden Boot]] and the league's [[Landon Donovan MVP Award|MVP award]]\u2014a first for the Revolution.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 11, 2005 |title=Twellman is choice for MVP |page=C6 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274681/twellman_is_choice_for_mvp/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116150116/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27274681/twellman_is_choice_for_mvp/ |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> Defender [[Michael Parkhurst]] earned the Rookie of the Year Award, while Twellman, Dempsey, and Joseph were named to the [[MLS Best XI]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Manza Young |first=Shalise |date=November 2, 2005 |title=Parkhurst top rookie in MLS |page=D8 |work=[[Providence Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |date=November 12, 2005 |title=RadioShack Best XI team announced on eve of MLS Cup |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051112&content_id=48172&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |publisher=Major League Soccer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060519070321/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051112&content_id=48172&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |archivedate=May 19, 2006 |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew England opened the playoffs in the Conference Semifinals against the [[New York/New Jersey MetroStars]], who clinched the 4th-seed berth on the last day of the season, mirroring the Revolution's performance in 2004.<ref name=\"NEMS\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 23, 2005 |title=Revolution take wrong turn |page=C2 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27293030/revolution_take_wrong_turn/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070117/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27293030/revolution_take_wrong_turn/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution lost 1\u20130 in the first leg at [[Giants Stadium]] in New Jersey,<ref name=\"NEMS\"/> but advanced on aggregate score after a 3\u20131 victory at home in Massachusetts with three second-half goals.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=October 30, 2005 |title=Best saved for last |page=C1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27293127/best_saved_for_last/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070012/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27293127/best_saved_for_last/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> In their fourth consecutive Eastern Conference final, New England faced the Chicago Fire at home and won 1\u20130 on a goal in the fourth minute by Clint Dempsey and a disallowed [[offside (association football)|offside]] goal.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 7, 2005 |title=Revolution celebrate flag day |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27293216/revolution_celebrate_flag_day/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117122326/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27293216/revolution_celebrate_flag_day/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Arroyave |first=Luis |date=November 7, 2005 |title=Offside ruling puts out Fire |page=1 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-11-07-0511070154-story.html |work=Chicago Tribune |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117122310/https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2005-11-07-0511070154-story.html |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Galaxy===\n\nThe Los Angeles Galaxy fired head coach [[Sigi Schmid]] midway during the 2004 season, only two years after leading them to their first cup title in 2002, despite the team's place at the top of the league.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=August 17, 2004 |title=Galaxy Decides to Fire Schmid |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/aug/17/sports/sp-galaxy17 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> His replacement for the remaining eight matches, former national team head coach [[Steve Sampson]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Gutierrez |first=Paul |date=August 19, 2004 |title=Sampson Is Part of the Galaxy |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/aug/19/sports/sp-galaxy19 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017155945/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/aug/19/sports/sp-galaxy19 |archive-date=October 17, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> led the team into a second-place finish in the Western Conference with only two wins and seven goals scored.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 17, 2004 |title=Powerless Galaxy Falls |page=D4 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/17/sports/sp-galaxy17 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> After defeating the [[Colorado Rapids]] in the Conference Semifinals, the Galaxy ended their season with a 2\u20130 loss to the first-place [[Kansas City Wizards]] in the Western Conference Final.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 31, 2004 |title=Galaxy Accomplishes Goals Against Rapids |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/31/sports/sp-galaxy31 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016222717/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/31/sports/sp-galaxy31 |archive-date=October 16, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=November 6, 2004 |title=Galaxy Hopes Quietly Slip Away to Wizards |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/nov/06/sports/sp-galaxy6 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151017120932/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/nov/06/sports/sp-galaxy6 |archive-date=October 17, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy rebuilt their roster ahead of the 2005 season, retaining only 12 of 28 players from the playoff run, and traded away [[Carlos Ruiz (Guatemalan footballer)|Carlos Ruiz]] to FC Dallas to sign returning American forward [[Landon Donovan]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=March 30, 2005 |title=They Form a Whole New Galaxy |page=D4 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/mar/30/sports/sp-galaxy30 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=April 1, 2005 |title=High-Flying Donovan Is Here to Stay With Galaxy |page=D1 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/apr/01/sports/sp-galaxy1 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121208181922/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/apr/01/sports/sp-galaxy1 |archive-date=December 8, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Los Angeles began the season with only two losses in their first eleven matches, but national team callups and injuries led to winless streaks in July and August.<ref>{{cite web |title=2005 Season in Review |url=https://www.lagalaxy.com/club/history/2005 |publisher=Los Angeles Galaxy |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070039/https://www.lagalaxy.com/club/history/2005 |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Galaxy also participated in the [[2005 U.S. Open Cup|U.S. Open Cup]], which it won in September against [[FC Dallas]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=September 29, 2005 |title=Gomez Is at the Right Spot at the Right Time |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/29/sports/sp-galaxy29 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923005517/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/sep/29/sports/sp-galaxy29 |archive-date=September 23, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The team finished the regular season with a 13\u201313\u20136 record, clinching the fourth seed in the Western Conference.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 16, 2005 |title=Galaxy Can't Stay With Earthquakes |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/16/sports/sp-galaxy16 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919084540/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/16/sports/sp-galaxy16 |archive-date=September 19, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Conference Semifinals, Los Angeles faced their [[California Cl\u00e1sico|in-state rivals]] and Supporters' Shield-winning [[San Jose Earthquakes]], who had won in the two team's last playoff meeting 5\u20134 on aggregate in [[2003 MLS Cup Playoffs|2003]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 29, 2005 |title=Galaxy Wants to Avoid a Close Call |page=D7 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/29/sports/sp-galaxy29 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080628012005/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/29/sports/sp-galaxy29 |archive-date=June 28, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Galaxy won the first leg 3\u20131 at their home, with two goals from Donovan against his former club, and drew the away leg 1\u20131 to advance 4\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=October 24, 2005 |title=Donovan Adds Insurance |page=D3 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/24/sports/sp-galaxy24 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407182210/http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/24/sports/sp-galaxy24 |archive-date=April 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |date=October 30, 2005 |title=Donovan motivated by 'idiots' in stands |page=D8 |work=[[The Mercury News]] |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/sports/soccer/13035332.htm |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051104085636/http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/sports/soccer/13035332.htm |archivedate=November 4, 2005 |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> Donovan then scored twice in Los Angeles's 2\u20130 over the Colorado Rapids in the Western Conference Final, sending the Galaxy to their fifth MLS Cup appearance.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=November 6, 2005 |title=Donovan Lifts Galaxy to Win |page=D5 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/nov/06/sports/sp-galaxy6 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Summary of results===\n\n:''Note: In all results below, the score of the finalist is given first (H: home; A: away).''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|[[New England Revolution]]\n!Round\n!colspan=4|[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|-\n|colspan=4 valign=top|1st place in [[2005 Major League Soccer season#Eastern Conference|Eastern Conference]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|'''[[New England Revolution]]'''\n|32||17||7||8||'''59'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[D.C. United]]\n|32||16||10||6||'''54'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|32||15||13||4||'''49'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[MetroStars]]\n|32||12||9||11||'''47'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|32||11||9||12||'''45'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Columbus Crew]]\n|32||11||16||5||'''38'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2005 MLS]}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|[[2005 Major League Soccer season|Regular season]]\n|colspan=4 valign=top|4th place in [[2005 Major League Soccer season#Western Conference|Western Conference]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none; font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:175px;\"|Team\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|W|Won}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|L|Lost}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|D|Drawn}}\n!width=\"20\"|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n|-style=\"background:#BBF1BD;\"\n|align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|32||18||4||10||'''64'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[FC Dallas]]\n|32||13||10||9||'''48'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|32||13||13||6||'''45'''\n|-style=\"background:#FFFEBB;\"\n|align=left|'''[[Los Angeles Galaxy]]'''\n|32||13||13||6||'''45'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Real Salt Lake]]\n|32||5||22||5||'''20'''\n|-\n|align=left|[[Chivas USA]]\n|32||4||22||6||'''18'''\n|}\n{{small|Source: [https://www.mlssoccer.com/standings/mls/2005 MLS]}}\n|- style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|[[2005 MLS Cup Playoffs|MLS Cup Playoffs]]\n|Opponent\n|{{tooltip|Agg.|Aggregate score}}\n|1st leg\n|2nd leg\n|-\n|align=left|[[MetroStars]]\n|3\u20132\n|{{nowrap|0\u20131 (A)}}\n|{{nowrap|3\u20131 (H)}}\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Semifinals\n|align=left|[[San Jose Earthquakes]]\n|4\u20132\n|{{nowrap|1\u20133 (H)}}\n|{{nowrap|1\u20131 (A)}}\n|-\n|align=left|[[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|colspan=3|1\u20130 (H)\n|style=\"background:#c1e0ff\"|Conference Final\n|align=left|[[Colorado Rapids]]\n|colspan=3|2\u20130 (A)\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\n\nThe MLS Cup final was televised in the United States on [[ESPN on ABC|ABC]] in English and Spanish using [[Second audio program|secondary audio programming]]. English play-by-play commentary was provided by [[JP Dellacamera]] with [[Color commentator|color analysis]] by [[Eric Wynalda]], reprising their roles at [[MLS Cup 2004]].<ref>{{cite news |date=November 12, 2005 |title=Cool breezes |page=C2 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref> [[Brandi Chastain]] provided sideline reporting, while [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]] anchored the pre-game and halftime shows. The Spanish language broadcast was provided by [[ESPN Deportes]] and included commentary from [[Randall Alvarez]] and [[Eduardo Biscayart]]. The match was also streamed via [[internet radio]] on MLSnet.com.<ref>{{cite press release |date=November 8, 2005 |title=MLS Cup 2005 reaches TV, radio audiences in English, Spanish |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/22/mls-cup-2005-reaches-tv-radio-audiences-english-spanish |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117070216/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2010/01/22/mls-cup-2005-reaches-tv-radio-audiences-english-spanish |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n\n===Summary===\n\nThe match, referred by [[Kevin Stott]], kicked off on a sunny day with temperatures of {{convert|75|F|C}}, at 12:30&nbsp;p.m. [[Central Time Zone|Central Time]].<ref name=\"DMN\"/><ref name=\"MLSN\">{{cite news |last=Halpin |first=Jason |date=November 13, 2005 |title=Extra! Extra! Galaxy capture MLS Cup |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48250&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060623183044/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48250&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |archivedate=June 23, 2006 |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> New England were named as the favorites heading into the MLS Cup, fielding an offensive lineup that was countered by Los Angeles's attacking midfielders.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 13, 2005 |title=Risk management: Title may hinge on midfield play |page=C13 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The Galaxy began the match with several attacks, including a [[Chip (association football)|lobbed shot]] into the goal in the sixth minute by forward [[Herculez Gomez]] that was ruled [[offside (association football)|offside]]. [[Chris Albright]] and [[Landon Donovan]] combined for an attempt in the 19th minute that drifted across the box.<ref name=\"MLSN\"/> The Revolution could not produce many attacks during the first half, with a lone shot near goal coming in the 29th minute on a missed header by [[Shalrie Joseph]] off a [[corner kick]].<ref name=\"Globe\">{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 14, 2005 |title=A case of deja blue |page=D1 |work=The Boston Globe |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/articles/2005/11/14/a_case_of_deja_blue/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051126133119/http://www.boston.com/sports/soccer/articles/2005/11/14/a_case_of_deja_blue/ |archivedate=November 26, 2005 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Fatigue\">{{cite news |last=Whitman |first=Robert |date=November 13, 2005 |title=Revolution succomb<!--[sic]--> to L.A., fatigue |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48303&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060521184658/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48303&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |archivedate=May 21, 2006 |accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy had two more chances to take the lead during the first half, with Gomez missing a shot from {{convert|12|yd|m}} in the 41st minute and Donovan's shot in stoppage time being saved by Revolution goalkeeper [[Matt Reis]].<ref name=\"Ives\">{{cite news |last=Galarcep |first=Ives |date=November 14, 2005 |title=Unlikely hero lifts Galaxy |page=D1 |work=Herald News |location=Passaic, New Jersey |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27418718/unlikely_hero_lifts_galaxy/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190120144058/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27418718/unlikely_hero_lifts_galaxy/ |archive-date=January 20, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref>\n\nThe Revolution began the second half with offensive pressure down the flanks, but failed to connect on crosses into the penalty area. New England's lone shot on goal during regulation time came from defender [[Jay Heaps]] in the 62nd minute, shooting into the hands of Los Angeles goalkeeper [[Kevin Hartman]].<ref name=\"MLSN\"/> The Revolution substituted [[Pat Noonan]] for midfielder [[Jos\u00e9 Cancela]], moving into a 4\u20132\u20132 with Twellman and Dempsey as strikers;<ref name=\"Globe\"/> the Galaxy responded by bringing on midfielder [[Guillermo Ram\u00edrez]] for [[Ned Grabavoy]] in the 66th minute.<ref name=\"MLSN\"/><ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news |last=Aron |first=Jamie |date=November 14, 2005 |title=Revs can't finish their Galaxy quest |page=D1 |work=[[Worcester Telegram & Gazette]] |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> The Galaxy had several chances to take a late lead, with a shot by Donovan in the 79th minute that was saved by [[Michael Parkhurst]] and an attempt by Gomez a minute later that passed over the goal.<ref name=\"MLSN\"/> [[Cobi Jones]] took the final regulation-time shot on goal for the Galaxy in the 83rd minute, which hit the crossbar of the goal.<ref name=\"MLSN\"/>\n\nCancela nearly gave New England a lead in the ninth minute of [[extra time]], hitting a half-volley from {{convert|22|yd|m}} that was deflected away from goal by Hartman.<ref name=\"Globe\"/> The Revolution pressed along the wings for another chance, including a cross by Albright that was headed wide by Donovan.<ref name=\"MLSN\"/> The winning goal for the Galaxy was scored in the 17th minute of extra time by Ram\u00edrez, who received a deflection from Reis and volleyed it from outside the penalty area.<ref name=\"AP\"/> After the overtime's short halftime, the Revolution missed several shots on goal while looking for an equalizing goal, but left themselves open to counterattacks by the Galaxy. Two shots from Donovan and Gomez were saved from close range by Reis in the 25th minute of extra time,<ref name=\"MLSN\"/> shortly before Cancela's shot was deflected away from goal by defender [[Ugo Ihemelu]] in stoppage time.<ref name=\"Globe\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Biglin |first=Mike |date=November 14, 2005 |title=Revs' title dreams: Lose championship to LA for second time |page=76 |work=[[Boston Herald]]}}</ref> Los Angeles won their second MLS Cup title, with the same scoreline and scoreless regulation as their previous victory over New England in 2002.<ref name=\"AP\"/>\n\n===Details===\n{{Football box\n| date         = {{Start date|2005|11|13|mf=y}}\n| time         = 12:30\n| team1        = [[New England Revolution]]\n| team2        = [[Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n| score        = 0\u20131\n| aet          = yes\n| goals2       = [[Guillermo Ram\u00edrez|Ram\u00edrez]] {{goal|107}}\n| stadium      = [[Toyota Stadium|Pizza Hut Park]], [[Frisco, Texas]]\n| attendance   = 21,193\n| referee      = [[Kevin Stott]]\n| report       = [https://www.mlssoccer.com/history/mls-cup/2005 Report]\n}}\n\n{| width=92% |\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = _adidasstripeswhite\n | pattern_b  = _MUNDIAL_WHITE\n | pattern_ra = _adidasstripeswhite\n | pattern_sh = _adidaswhite2011\n | leftarm    = 000030\n | body       = 000030\n | rightarm   = 000030\n | shorts     = 000030\n | socks      = 000030\n | title      = New England Revolution\n}}\n|{{Football kit\n | pattern_la = \n | pattern_b  = _GALAXY_05h\n | pattern_ra = _GALAXY_05h\n | pattern_sh = \n | pattern_so = \n | leftarm    = FFC20E\n | body       = FFFFFF\n | rightarm   = FFFFFF\n | shorts     = 27563D\n | socks      = FFC20E\n | title      = Los Angeles Galaxy\n}}\n|}\n\n{| style=\"w