[[Marcelo Saragosa]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''29'''||{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Ednaldo da Concei\u00e7\u00e3o]] || || {{subon|109}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|USA}} [[Alan Gordon (soccer)|Alan Gordon]] || || {{subon|119}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=4|{{flagicon|USA}} [[Steve Sampson]]\n|}\n|}\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|\n'''MLS Cup Most Valuable Player:'''\n<br />\n{{flagicon|GUA}} [[Guillermo Ram\u00edrez]] (Los Angeles Galaxy)\n|}\n\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|\n'''Assistant referees:'''\n<br />Chris Strickland (United States)\n<br />Greg Barkey (United States)\n<br />'''Fourth official:'''\n<br />[[Ricardo Valenzuela (referee)|Ricardo Valenzuela]] (United States)\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nThe Los Angeles Galaxy became the third team in MLS history to win both an MLS Cup and the U.S. Open Cup in the same season, following [[D.C. United]] in 1996 and the Chicago Fire in 1998.<ref name=\"OCR\">{{cite news |last=Calhoun |first=Damian |date=November 14, 2005 |title=All's well that ends well for Ramirez |page=A1 |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2005/11/14/alls-well-that-ends-well-for-ramirez/ |work=[[Orange County Register]] |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117232504/https://www.ocregister.com/2005/11/14/alls-well-that-ends-well-for-ramirez/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Guillermo Ram\u00edrez]] was named the MLS Cup MVP for his performance, which contrasted with his struggles to score during the regular season. He attempted 62 shots from open play and was unable to convert.<ref>{{cite news |last=Halpin |first=Jason |date=November 13, 2005 |title=Weight off Pando's MVP shoulders |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48284&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708142142/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48284&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |archivedate=July 8, 2006 |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> The Galaxy declined to continue his loan and Ram\u00edrez returned the following season to [[CSD Municipal]] in Guatemala.<ref>{{cite news |last=Abrams |first=Jonathan |date=June 25, 2006 |title=Different Days for the Galaxy |page=D11 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/25/sports/sp-galaxy25 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415052156/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/25/sports/sp-galaxy25 |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The match featured 10 [[Yellow card (sport)|yellow card]]s, doubling the previous MLS Cup record set in [[MLS Cup 2001|2001]], was the third to be decided by a single goal, and the second to be scoreless before overtime after the 2002 final.<ref name=\"DMN\">{{cite news |last=Davis |first=Steve |date=November 14, 2005 |title=Only takes one: Unlikely hero's overtime goal gives Galaxy the title |page=C1 |work=Dallas Morning News}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=November 13, 2005 |title=MLS Cup 2005 postgame notes |url=http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48275&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |work=MLSnet.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060722131234/http://www.mlsnet.com/MLS/news/mls_events_news.jsp?ymd=20051113&content_id=48275&vkey=mlscup2005&fext=.jsp |archivedate=July 22, 2006 |accessdate=January 16, 2019}}</ref> The match's attendance of 21,193 was a sellout crowd, and included hundreds of traveling supporters from New England and 100 employees brought by Revolution owner [[Robert Kraft]], but remains the lowest for an MLS Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |date=December 2017 |title=MLS Cup 2017 Game Guide: Toronto FC vs. Seattle Sounders FC |page=132 |url=https://seattle-mp7static.mlsdigital.net/elfinderimages/2016/Media/Game%20Guides/MLSCUP2017.pdf |publisher=Major League Soccer |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181115153434/https://seattle-mp7static.mlsdigital.net/elfinderimages/2016/Media/Game%20Guides/MLSCUP2017.pdf |archive-date=November 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 15, 2005 |title='05 qualifies as success for Revolution |page=D3 |work=The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\nBoth finalists qualified for the quarterfinals of the [[2006 CONCACAF Champions' Cup]], played during the following preseason against Costa Rican teams. The Galaxy lost 3\u20132 to [[Deportivo Saprissa]], while the Revolution fell 1\u20130 to [[Liga Deportiva Alajuelense|Alajuelense]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Grahame L. |date=March 9, 2006 |title=Galaxy, Revolution Out of CONCACAF Event |page=D10 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/mar/09/sports/sp-soccer9 |work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=March 9, 2006 |title=Hernandez's free kick eliminates Revolution |page=C7 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27308745/hernandezs_free_kick_eliminates/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117174305/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27308745/hernandezs_free_kick_eliminates/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref> The Revolution were also finalists in the next two MLS Cups, losing both to the [[Houston Dynamo]] (formed from the San Jose Earthquakes) on [[penalty shootout (association football)|penalty kicks]] at Pizza Hut Park in [[MLS Cup 2006|2006]] and in regulation time at RFK Memorial Stadium in Washington, D.C. in [[MLS Cup 2007|2007]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Dell'Apa |first=Frank |date=November 21, 2007 |title=Revolution scored style points but were overpowered |page=D11 |work=The Boston Globe |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27308804/revolution_scored_style_points_but_were/ |via=Newspapers.com |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117174153/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/27308804/revolution_scored_style_points_but_were/ |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }} {{free access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=White |first=Joseph |date=November 19, 2007 |title=Dynamo rally for MLS crown |page=D2 |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/695228968/Dynamo-rally-for-MLS-crown.html |work=[[Deseret News]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190117175659/https://www.deseretnews.com/article/695228968/Dynamo-rally-for-MLS-crown.html |archive-date=January 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Los Angeles and New England would meet again in the [[MLS Cup 2014|2014 final]], which marked the Galaxy's fifth title and the Revolution's fifth loss.<ref>{{cite news |last=Powers |first=John |date=December 8, 2014 |title=Galaxy defeat Revolution for record fifth MLS title |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |work=The Boston Globe |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107185307/https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/12/07/galaxy-defeat-revolution-for-record-fifth-mls-title/QXMrUO8NT5sTEKPW5Un1UL/story.html |archive-date=November 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{MLSCup}}\n{{2005 in American soccer}}\n{{Los Angeles Galaxy matches}}\n{{New England Revolution matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2005 Mls Cup}}\n[[Category:MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:2005 Major League Soccer season|*]]\n[[Category:LA Galaxy matches|MLS Cup 2005]]\n[[Category:New England Revolution matches|MLS Cup 2005]]\n[[Category:November 2005 sports events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2005 in sports in Texas|MLS Cup]]\n[[Category:Sports in Frisco, Texas]]\n[[Category:Soccer in Texas]]\n", "name_user": "SounderBruce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSummary of results:adding source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MLS_Cup_2005"}
{"title_page": "Greatest Hits Vol. 2 (ABBA album)", "text_new": "{{short description|1979 ABBA compilation album}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Greatest Hits Vol. 2\n| type       = Greatest hits\n| artist     = [[ABBA]]\n| cover      = ABBA - Greatest Hits Vol. 2 (Polar).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|1979|10|29}}\n| recorded   = October 1974 \u2013 August 1979\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Disco music|disco]]\n| length     = 58:25\n| label      = [[Polar Music|Polar]] (Sweden)<br />[[Epic Records|Epic]] (UK)<br />[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] (US)\n| producer   = [[Benny Andersson]] & [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]\n| prev_title = [[Voulez-Vous]]\n| prev_year  = 1979\n| next_title = [[Gracias Por La M\u00fasica (album)|Gracias Por La M\u00fasica]]\n| next_year  = 1980\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Greatest Hits Vol. 2\n | type        = compilation\n | single1     = [[Summer Night City]]\n | single1date = 6 September 1978 (Sweden)/16 September 1978 (UK)\n | single2     = [[Gimme! Gimme! Gimme! (A Man After Midnight)]]\n | single2date = October 2, 1979\n | single3     = [[The King Has Lost His Crown]]\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score =  {{Rating|2|5}} <ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r38|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating-Christgau|C}}<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: A|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=A&bk=70|accessdate=12 September 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Greatest Hits Vol. 2''''' is a compilation album by [[Sweden|Swedish]] pop group [[ABBA]], released in October 1979 to coincide with their tour of North America and Europe (taking place between September and November 1979). It was ABBA's second chart-topping album of the year, the first being ''[[Voulez-Vous]]'', and contained the brand new single \"[[Gimme! Gimme! Gimme! (A Man After Midnight)]]\", recorded in August 1979.\n\nA round-up of ABBA\u2019s hits since their first compilation album (released in 1975), the album exclusively included material recorded between the years 1976 and 1979 (albums ''[[Arrival (ABBA album)|Arrival]]'', ''[[ABBA: The Album|The Album]]'' and ''[[Voulez-Vous]]'' plus non-album single \"[[Summer Night City]]\") - with one exception, \"Rock Me\" from 1975 album ''[[ABBA (album)|ABBA]]'', issued as a single and became a top 5 hit in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] after the release of the band's first hits package ''[[Greatest Hits (ABBA album)|Greatest Hits]]'' and also part of the setlist on the 1979 world tour.\n\n\"[[Angeleyes]]\" was included primarily due to its success as a single in the UK, where it was the lead track of a double A-side with \"[[Voulez-Vous (song)|Voulez-Vous]]\". Elsewhere, \"Voulez-Vous\" had been the A-side in its own right but it was not included on the album.  However, the track \"I Wonder (Departure)\" was not believed to have been released as a single anywhere, but was featured.\n\n''Greatest Hits Vol. 2'' received massive commercial success in [[Japan]], selling in excess of 920,000 units on the chart (it was the best-selling album by non-domestic artists at the time, until [[Michael Jackson]]'s ''[[Thriller (Michael Jackson album)|Thriller]]''  each sold over 1 million copies in the 1980s).  It is certified Gold in the U.S.\n\n''Greatest Hits Vol. 2 ''was released on CD in 1982 by Polydor but was deleted from their ABBA CD range in 1992 when it was replaced with ''[[Gold: Greatest Hits|ABBA Gold]]''. It was also released in the US by Atlantic Records in 1983 with the same mastering as the Polydor CD but was discontinued there in the late 1980s as well.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by [[Benny Andersson]] & [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]], except where noted.\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| headline = Side A\n| title1 = [[Gimme! Gimme! Gimme! (A Man After Midnight)]]\n| length1 = 4:49\n| title2 = [[Knowing Me, Knowing You]]\n| writer2 = Andersson, [[Stig Anderson]], Ulvaeus\n| length2 = 4:01\n| title3 = [[Take a Chance on Me]]\n| length3 = 3:58\n| title4 = [[Money, Money, Money]]\n| length4 = 3:06\n| title5 = [[Rock_Me_(ABBA_song)|Rock Me]]\n| length5 = 3:03\n| title6 = [[Eagle (song)|Eagle]]\n| length6 = 5:48\n| title7 = [[Angeleyes]]\n| length7 = 4:17\n| title8 =\n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = \n}}{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| headline = Side B\n| title1 = [[Dancing Queen]]\n| writer1 = Andersson, Anderson, Ulvaeus\n| length1 = 3:48\n| title2 = [[Does Your Mother Know]]\n| length2 = 3:12\n| title3 = [[Chiquitita]]\n| length3 = 5:21\n| title4 = [[Summer Night City]]\n| length4 = 3:31\n| title5 = [[I Wonder (Departure)]]\n| writer5 = Andersson, Anderson, Ulvaeus\n| length5 = 4:31\n| title6 = [[The Name of the Game (ABBA song)|The Name of the Game]]\n| writer6 = Andersson, Anderson, Ulvaeus\n| length6 = 4:50\n| title7 = [[Thank You for the Music]]\n| length7 = 3:47\n| title8 = \n| length8 = \n| title9 = \n| length9 = \n| title10 = \n| length10 = \n| title11 = \n| length11 = \n| title12 = \n| length12 = \n| title13 = \n| length13 = \n| title14 = \n| length14 = \n| title15 = \n| length15 = \n| title16 = \n| length16 = \n| title17 = \n| length17 = \n| title18 = \n| length18 = \n| title19 = \n| length19 = \n| title20 = \n| length20 = \n| total_length = \n}}\n\n==Singles==\n# \"Summer Night City/Medley\" (September 1978)\n# \"Gimme Gimme Gimme/The King Has Lost His Crown\" (October 1979)\n\n==Personnel==\n{{div col}}\n*[[Agnetha F\u00e4ltskog]] - lead vocals {{small|(1, 10, 14)}}, co-lead vocals {{small|(3, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 13)}}, backing vocals\n*[[Anni-Frid Lyngstad]] - lead vocals {{small|(2, 4, 12)}}, co-lead vocals {{small|(3, 6, 7, 8, 9, 11, 13)}}, backing vocals\n*[[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]] - lead vocals {{small|(5, 9, 11)}}, [[Steel-string guitar|acoustic guitar]], [[electric guitar]], backing vocals\n*[[Benny Andersson]] - [[keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[synthesizer]], backing vocals\n*Rolf Alex - drums\n*[[Ola Brunkert]] - drums\n*Lars Carlsson - horn\n*Christer Danielson - horn\n*Andrew Eijas - horn\n*Malando Gassama - percussion\n*[[Rutger Gunnarsson]] - bass\n*Gloria Lundell - harp\n*Roger Palm - drums\n*Halldor Palsson - saxophone\n*Janne Schaffer - guitar\n*Bengt Sundberg - horn\n*\u00c5ke Sundqvist - percussion\n*Mike Watson - bass\n*Lasse Wellander - guitar\n*Gunnar Wenneborg - horn\n*Kajtek Wojciechowski - saxophone\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n*Producers: Benny Andersson & Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus\n*Arrangers: Benny Andersson & Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus\n*Engineer: [[Michael B. Tretow]]\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1979\u201381)\n!Position\n!Weeks\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"AUS\">{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= [[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970-1992]] |year= 1993 |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], N.S.W. |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|20\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|Austrian Albums Chart<ref name=\"atchart\">{{cite web|title= ABBA - Greatest Hits Vol.2 - austriancharts.at|url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=ABBA&titel=Greatest+Hits+Vol%2E+2&cat=a|accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|align=\"center\"|34\n|-\n|Belgium\n